\id LUK Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h Luke
\mt1 The Holy Gospel of Jesus Christ according to Luke.
\c 1
\p
\v 1 \sc Because\sc* many have gone about to compile a narration of the things that have been accomplished among us;
\v 2 according as they have delivered unto us, who from the beginning themselves saw and were ministers of the word;
\v 3 it seemed good also unto me having diligently attained to all things from the beginning, to write to thee in order, good Theophilus,
\v 4 that thou mayst know the verity of those words whereof thou hast been instructed.
\v 5 There was in the days of Herod the king of Jewry, a certain Priest named Zacharie, of the course of Abia; & his wife of the daughters of Aaron, and her name Elizabeth. \f + \fr 1:5 \ft The Gospel upon the eve of S. John Baptist.\f*
\v 6 And they were both just before God, walking in all the commandments and justifications of our Lord without blame,
\v 7 and they had no son: for that Elizabeth was barren, and both were well striken in their days.
\v 8 And it came to pass, when he executed the priestly function in the order of his course before God,
\v 9 according to the custom of the Priestly function, he went forth by lot to offer incense, entering into the temple of our Lord;
\v 10 and all the multitude of the people was praying without at the hour of the incense. \f + \fr 1:10 \ft We see here that the Priest did his duty within, the people in the mean time praying without: and that the Priests functions did profit them, though they neither heard nor saw his doings.\f*
\v 11 And there appeared to him an Angel of our Lord, standing on the right hand of the Altar of incense.
\v 12 And Zacharie was troubled, seeing him; and fear fell upon him.
\v 13 But the Angel said to him: Fear not Zacharie, for thy prayer is heard; and thy wife Elizabeth shall bear thee a son and thou shalt call his name John:
\v 14 and thou shalt have joy and exultation, and many shall rejoice in his nativity.
\v 15 For he shall be great before our Lord; and wine and sicer he shall not drink; and he shall be replenished with the Holy Ghost even from his mother's womb. \f + \fr 1:15 \ft This abstinence foretold and prescribed by the Angel, sheweth that it is a worthy thing, and an act of religion in S. John, as it was in the Nazarites.\f*
\v 16 And he shall convert many of the children of Israel to the Lord their God.
\v 17 And he shall go before him in the spirit and virtue of Elias, that he may convert the hearts of the fathers unto the children, and the incredulous to the wisdom of the just, to prepare unto the Lord a perfect people.
\v 18 And Zacharie said to the Angel: Whereby shall I know this? For I am old; and my wife is well striken in her days.
\v 19 And the Angel answering said to him: I am Gabriel that assist before God; and am sent to speak to thee, and to evangelize these things to thee.
\v 20 And behold, thou shalt be dumb, and shalt not be able to speak until the day wherein these things shall be done; for-because thou hast not believed my words, which shall be fulfilled in their time. \f + \fr 1:20 \ft Zachary punished for doubting of the Angel's word.\f*
\v 21 And the people was expecting Zacharie; and they marveled that he made tarriance in the temple.
\v 22 And coming forth he could not speak to them, and they knew that he had seen a vision in the temple. And he made signs to them, and remained dumb.
\v 23 And it came to pass, after the days of his office were expired, he departed into his house.
\v 24 And after these days Elizabeth his wife conceived; and hid herself five months, saying:
\v 25 For thus hath our Lord done to me in the days wherein he had respect to take away my reproach among men.
\v 26 And in the sixth month, the Angel Gabriel was sent of God into a city of Galilee, called Nazareth, \f + \fr 1:26 \ft b The Gospel upon the Annunciation of our Lady, March 25. And on the Wednesday of Imber week in Advent. And for a Votive Mass of our Lady in Advent.\f*
\v 27 to a virgin despoused to a man whose name was Joseph, of the house of David; and the virgin's name was \sc Mary\sc*.
\v 28 And the Angel being entered in, said unto her: \add \sc Hail\sc* full of grace, our Lord is with thee: blessed art thou among women.\add* \f + \fr 1:28 \ft The beginning of the AVE MARIE. See the rest v. 42.\f*
\v 29 Who having heard, was troubled at his saying, and thought what manner of salutation this should be.
\v 30 And the Angel said to her: Fear not \sc Mary\sc*, for thou hast found grace with God.
\v 31 Behold thou shalt conceive in thy womb, and shalt bear a Son; and thou shalt call his name \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 32 He shall be great, and shall be called the Son of the most High, and our Lord God shall give him the seat of David his father:
\v 33 and he shall reign in the house of Jacob for ever, and of his Kingdom there shall be no end.
\v 34 And \sc Mary\sc* said to the Angel: How shall this be done, because I know not man? \f + \fr 1:34 \ft She doubted not of the thing as Zachary, but inquired of the means.\f*
\v 35 And the Angel answering, said to her: The Holy Ghost shall come upon thee, and the power of the most High shall overshadow thee. And therefore also that which of thee shall be born Holy, shall be called the Son of God.
\v 36 And behold Elizabeth thy cousin, she also hath conceived a Son in her old age; and this month, is the sixth to her that is called barren;
\v 37 because there shall not be impossible with God any word.
\v 38 And \sc Mary\sc* said, \add \sc Behold\sc* the handmaid of our Lord, be it done to me according to thy word.\add* And the Angel departed from her. \f + \fr 1:38 \ft At this very moment when the B. Virgin gave consent, she conceived him perfect God and perfect man.\f*
\v 39 And \sc Mary\sc* rising up in those days, went unto the hill country with speed into a city of Juda. \f + \fr 1:39 \ft The Gospel upon the Visitation of our Lady, Iul. 2. And upon the Imber Friday in Advent.\f*
\v 40 And she entered into the house of Zacharie, and saluted Elizabeth.
\v 41 And it came to pass; as Elizabeth heard the salutation of \sc Mary\sc*, the infant did leap in her womb. And Elizabeth was replenished with the Holy Ghost: \f + \fr 1:41 \ft John the Baptist being yet in his mother's womb, rejoiced and acknowledged the presence of Christ and his mother.\f*
\v 42 and she cried out with a loud voice, and said, \add \sc Blessed\sc* art thou among women, and blessed is the fruit of thy womb.\add*
\v 43 And whence is this to me, that the mother of my Lord doth come to me?
\v 44 For behold as the voice of thy salutation sounded in mine ears, the infant in my womb did leap for joy.
\v 45 And Blessed is she that believed because those things shall be accomplished that were spoken to her by our Lord.
\v 46 And \sc Mary\sc* said: \add MY \sc Soul\sc* doth magnify our Lord:\add* \f + \fr 1:46 \ft MAGNIFICAT at Evensong.\f*
\v 47 \add And my spirit hath rejoiced in God my Saviour.\add*
\v 48 \add Because he hath regarded the humility of his handmaid; for behold from hence forth \add* \add all generations shall call me blessed.\add* \f + \fr 1:48 \ft Have the Protestants had always generations to fulfill this prophecy? Or do they call her blessed, that derogate what they can from her graces, blessings, and all her honour?\f*
\v 49 \add Because he that is mighty hath done great things to me: and holy is his name.\add*
\v 50 \add And his mercy from generation unto generations, to them that fear him.\add*
\v 51 \add He hath shewed might in his arm: he hath dispersed the proud in the conceit of their heart.\add*
\v 52 \add He hath deposed the mighty from their seat, & hath exalted the humble.\add*
\v 53 \add The hungry he hath filled with good things: and the rich he hath sent away empty.\add*
\v 54 \add He hath received Israel his child, being mindful of his mercy,\add*
\v 55 \add As he spake to our fathers, to Abraham and his seed for ever.\add*
\v 56 And \sc Mary\sc* tarried with her about three months: and she returned into her house.
\v 57 And Elizabeth's full time was come to be delivered; and she bare a son. \f + \fr 1:57 \ft The Gospel upon the Nativity of S. John Baptist Iun. 24. called Midsummer day.\f*
\v 58 And her neighbours and kinsfolk heard that our Lord did magnify his mercy with her, and they did congratulate her.
\v 59 And it came to pass; on the eighth day they came to circumcise the child, and they called him by his father's name Zacharie.
\v 60 And his mother answering, said: Not so, but he shall be called John.
\v 61 And they said to her, That there is none in thy kindred that is called by this name.
\v 62 And they made signs to his father, what he would have him called.
\v 63 And demanding a writing table, he wrote, saying: John is his name. And they all marveled.
\v 64 And forthwith his mouth was opened, and his tongue, and he spake blessing God.
\v 65 And fear came upon all their neighbours; and all these things were bruited over all the hill-country of Jewry:
\v 66 and all that had heard, laid them up in their heart, saying: What an one, trow ye, shall this child be? For the hand of our Lord was with him.
\v 67 And Zacharie his father was replenished with the Holy Ghost; and he prophesied, saying:
\v 68 \add \sc Blessed be Our Lord\sc* God of Israel: because he hath visited and wrought the redemption of his people:\add* \f + \fr 1:68 \ft BENEDICTUS at Lauds.\f*
\v 69 \add And hath erected the horn of salvation to us, in the\add* house of David his servant.
\v 70 \add As he spake by the mouth of his holy Prophets, that are from the beginning:\add*
\v 71 \add Salvation from our enemies, and from the hand of all that hate us:\add*
\v 72 \add To work mercy with our fathers; and to remember his holy testament,\add*
\v 73 \add The oath which he sware to Abraham our father,\add*
\v 74 \add that he would give to us. That without fear being delivered from the hand of our enemies, we may serve him,\add*
\v 75 \add In holiness and justice before him, all our days.\add*
\v 76 \add And thou child, shalt be called the Prophet of the Highest: for \add* \add thou shalt go before the face of our Lord to prepare his ways.\add*
\v 77 \add To give knowledge of salvation to his people, unto remission of their sins,\add*
\v 78 \add Through the bowels of the mercy of our God, in which the \add* \add Orient, from on high, hath visited us.\add*
\v 79 \add To illuminate them that sit in darkness, and in the shadow of death: to direct our feet into the way of peace.\add*
\v 80 And the child grew, and was strengthened in spirit, and was in the deserts until the day of his manifestation to Israel. \f + \fr 1:80 \ft Mark that he was a voluntary Eremite, and chose to be solitary from a child, till he was to preach to the people, in so much that antiquity counted him the first Eremite. Hiero. in vit. Pauli.\f*
\c 2
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass, in those days there came forth an Edict from Cæsar Augustus that the whole world should be enrolled. \f + \fr 2:1 \ft The Gospel at the first Mass upon Christmas day.\f* \f + \fr 2:1 \ft In the year, from the creation of the world 5199: from Noe's flood, 2957: from the Nativity of Abraham, 2015: from Moyses and the coming forth of the people of Israel out of Ægypt, 1510: from David anointed king, 1032: from the first Olympias, 800: from the building of Rome, 752: hebdomada 63 according to the prophecy of Daniel (c. 9) that is, in the year 440 or there about: in the sixth Age of the world, when there was universal peace in all the world: the eternal God and son of the eternal Father, meaning to consecrate and sanctify the world with his most blessed coming, being conceived of the Holy Ghost, nine months after his conception, JESUS CHRIST the son of God is born in Bethlehem of Juda, in the year of Cæsar Augustus 42. Usuard. in martyrol. Decemb. 25. according to the common ancient supputation.\f*
\v 2 This first enrolling was made by the President of Syria Cyrinus.
\v 3 And all went to be enrolled, every one into his own city.
\v 4 And Joseph also went up from Galilee out of the city of Nazareth into Jewry, to the city of David that is called Beth-lehem: for because he was of the house and family of David,
\v 5 to be enrolled with \sc Mary\sc* his despoused wife that was with child.
\v 6 And it came to pass, when they were there, her days were fully come that she should be delivered.
\v 7 And she brought forth her first begotten son, and swaddled him in cloths, and laid him down in a manger; because there was not place for them in the inn.
\v 8 And there were in the same country shepherds watching, and keeping the night watches over their flock.
\v 9 And behold, an Angel of our Lord stood beside them, and the brightness of God did shine round about them, and they feared with a great fear.
\v 10 And the Angel said to them: Fear not; for behold I evangelize to you great joy, that shall be to all the people:
\v 11 because this day is born to you a \sc Saviour\sc* which is Christ our Lord, in the city of David.
\v 12 And this shall be a sign to you; You shall find the infant swaddled in cloths, and laid in a manger.
\v 13 And suddenly there was with the Angel a multitude of the heavenly army, praising God, and saying,
\v 14 \add Glory in the highest to God: and in earth peace to men of good will.\add* \f + \fr 2:14 \ft GLORIA IN EXCELSIS at Mass.\f*
\v 15 And it came to pass, after the Angels departed from them into Heaven, the shepherds spake one to another: Let us go over to Bethlehem, and let us see this word that is done, which our Lord hath shewed to us. \f + \fr 2:15 \ft b The Gospel at the second Mass upon Christmas day. And within the Octave. And for a Votive of our Lady from Christmas to Candlemas.\f*
\v 16 And they came with speed; and they found \sc Mary\sc* and Joseph, and the infant laid in the manger.
\v 17 And seeing it, they understood of the word that had been spoken to them concerning this child.
\v 18 And all that heard, did marvel; and concerning those things that were reported to them by the shepherds.
\v 19 But \sc Mary\sc* kept all these words, conferring them in her heart.
\v 20 And the shepherds returned, glorifying and praising God in all things that they had heard, and seen, as it was said to them.
\v 21 And after eight days were expired, that the child should be circumcised; his name was called \sc Jesus\sc*, which was called by the Angel, before that he was conceived in the womb. \f + \fr 2:21 \ft c The Gospel upon the Circumcision of our Lord Ian. 1.\f*
\v 22 And after the days were fully ended of her purification according to the law of Moyses, they carried him into Jerusalem, to present him to our Lord \f + \fr 2:22 \ft d The Gospel upon the Purification of our Lady or Candlemas day. Feb 2.\f*
\v 23 (as it is written in the law of our Lord, \add That every male opening the matrice, shall be called holy to the Lord.\add* )
\v 24 and to give a sacrifice according as it is written in the law of our Lord, a pair of turtles, or two young pigeons.
\v 25 And behold there was a man in Jerusalem named Simeon, and this man was just and religious, expecting the consolation of Israel: and the Holy Ghost was in him.
\v 26 And he had received an answer of the Holy Ghost, that he should not see death unless he saw first the \sc Christ\sc* of our Lord.
\v 27 And he came in Spirit into the temple. And when his parents brought in the child \sc Jesus\sc*, to do according to the custom of the Law for him,
\v 28 he also took him into his arms, and blessed God, and said:
\v 29 \add \sc Now Thou\sc* doest dismiss thy servant O Lord, according to thy word in peace.\add* \f + \fr 2:29 \ft NUNC DIMITTIS at Compline.\f*
\v 30 \add Because mine eyes have seen thy \sc Salvation\sc*,\add*
\v 31 \add Which thou hast prepared before the face of all peoples:\add*
\v 32 \add A light to the revelation of the Gentiles, & the glory of thy people Israel.\add*
\v 33 And his father and mother were marveling upon those things which were spoken concerning him.
\v 34 And Simeon blessed them, and said to \sc Mary\sc* his mother: Behold this is set unto the ruin, and unto the resurrection of many in Israel, & for a sign which shall be contradicted,
\v 35 and thine own soul shall a sword pierce, that out of many hearts cogitations may be revealed. \f + \fr 2:35 \ft Simeon prophesied not only of Christ but also of our B. Lady, of all her sorrows: wherein she was always partaker with our Saviour, from his flight into Ægypt even to his death.\f*
\v 36 And there was Anne a prophetess, the daughter of Phanuel, of the tribe of Aser: she was far striken in days, and had lived with her husband seven years from her virginity.
\v 37 And she was a widow until eighty and four years; who departed not from the temple, by fastings and prayers serving night and day. \f + \fr 2:37 \ft λατρέυουσα.\f*
\v 38 And she at the same hour suddenly coming in, confessed to our Lord; and spake of him to all that expected the redemption of Israel.
\v 39 And after they had wholly done all things according to the law of our Lord, they returned into Galilee, into their city Nazareth.
\v 40 And the child grew, and waxed strong: full of wisdom, and the grace of God was in him. \f + \fr 2:40 \ft strong in spirit:\f*
\v 41 And his parents went every year unto Jerusalem, at the solemn day of Pasch.
\v 42 And when he was twelve years old, they going up into Jerusalem according to the custom of the festival day; \f + \fr 2:42 \ft The Gospel upon the first Sunday after the Epiphany.\f*
\v 43 and having ended the days, when they returned, the child \sc Jesus\sc* remained in Jerusalem: and his parents knew it not.
\v 44 And thinking that he was in the company, they came a day's journey, and sought him among their kinsfolk and acquaintance.
\v 45 And not finding him, they returned into Jerusalem, seeking him.
\v 46 And it came to pass, after three days they found him in the temple sitting in the midst of the Doctors, hearing them and asking them.
\v 47 And all were astonished that heard him, upon his wisdom & answers.
\v 48 And seeing him, they wondered. And his mother said to him: Son, why hast thou so done to us? Behold thy father and I sorrowing did seek thee.
\v 49 And he said to them: What is it that you sought me? Did you not know, that I must be about those things which are my Father's?
\v 50 And they understood not the word that he spake unto them.
\v 51 And he went down with them, and came to Nazareth; and was subject to them. And his mother kept all these words in her heart.
\v 52 And \sc Jesus\sc* proceeded in wisdom and age, and grace with God and men.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* in the fifteenth year of the empire of Tiberius Cæsar, Pontius Pilate being Governor of Jewry, and Herod being Tetrarch of Galilee, and Philip his brother Tetrarch of Iturea and the country Trachonitis, and Lysanias Tetrarch of Abilina, \f + \fr 3:1 \ft The Gospel upon Imber Saturday in Advent. And on the 4. Sunday in Advent.\f*
\v 2 under the high Priests Annas and Caiphas: the word of our Lord was made upon John the son of Zacharie, in the desert.
\v 3 And he came into all the country of Jordan, preaching the baptism of penance unto remission of sins; as it is written in the book of the sayings of Esay the Prophet: \f + \fr 3:3 \ft Penance prepareth the way to Christ.\f*
\v 4 \add A voice of one crying in the desert; prepare the way of our Lord, make straight his paths.\add*
\v 5 \add Every valley shall be filled; and every mountain and hill shall be made low, and crooked things shall become straight; and rough ways, plain:\add*
\v 6 \add And all flesh shall see the \sc Salvation\sc* of God.\add*
\v 7 He said therefore to the multitudes that went forth to be baptized of him: Ye vipers' broods, who hath shewed you to flee from the wrath to come?
\v 8 Yield therefore fruits worthy of penance; and do ye not begin to say, we have Abraham, to our father. For I tell you, that God is able of these stones to raise up children to Abraham. \f + \fr 3:8 \ft Fruits of penance be works satisfactory.\f*
\v 9 And now the axe is put to the root of the trees. Every tree therefore that yieldeth not good fruit, shall be cut down, and cast into fire. \f + \fr 3:9 \ft Aman without good works is unfruitful, and shall be cast into everlasting fire.\f* \f + \fr 3:9 \ft is\f*
\v 10 And the multitudes asked him, saying: What shall we do then?
\v 11 And he answering, said unto them: He that hath two coats, let him give to him that hath not; and he that hath meat, let him do likewise. \f + \fr 3:11 \ft Alms counseled or enjoined for sins and to avoid damnation.\f*
\v 12 And the Publicans also came to be baptized, and said to him: Master, what shall we do?
\v 13 But he said to them: Do nothing more than that which is appointed you.
\v 14 And the soldiers also asked him, saying: What shall we also do? And he said to them: Vex not, neither calumniate any man; and be content with your stipends.
\v 15 And the people imagining, and all men thinking in their hearts of John, lest perhaps he were Christ: \f + \fr 3:15 \ft John was so holy that many might by error easily think he was Christ.\f*
\v 16 John answered, saying unto all: I indeed baptize you with water, but there shall come a mightier than I, whose latchet of his shoes I am not worthy to loose; he shall baptize you in the Holy Ghost and fire: \f + \fr 3:16 \ft How say then the Heretics that the baptism of Christ is of no greater virtue than John's?\f* \f + \fr 3:16 \ft cometh\f*
\v 17 whose fan is in his hand, and he will purge his floor; and will gather the wheat into his barn, but the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire.
\v 18 Many other things also exhorting did he evangelize to the people.
\v 19 And Herod the Tetrarch, when he was rebuked of him for Herodias his brother's wife, and for all the evils which Herod did: \f + \fr 3:19 \ft brother Philip's\f*
\v 20 He added this also above all, and shut up John into prison.
\v 21 And it came to pass when all the people was baptized, \sc Jesus\sc* also being baptized and praying, Heaven was opened:
\v 22 And the Holy Ghost descended in corporal shape as a dove upon him: and a voice from Heaven was made: Thou art my beloved Son, in thee I am well pleased.
\v 23 And \sc Jesus\sc* himself was beginning to be about thirty years old: as it was thought, the son of Joseph, who was of Heli,
\v 24 who was of Matthat, who was of Levi, who was of Melchi, who was of Ianne, who was of Joseph,
\v 25 who was of Matthathias, who was of Amos, who was of Naum, who was of Hesli, who was of Nagge,
\v 26 who was of Mahath, who was of Matthathias, who was of Semei, who was of Joseph, who was of Juda,
\v 27 who was of Johanna, who was of Resa, who was of Zorobabel, who was of Salathiel, who was of Neri,
\v 28 who was of Melchi, who was of Addi, who was of Cosam, who was of Elmadan, who was of Her,
\v 29 who was of Jesus, who was of Eliezer, who was of Iorim, who was of Matthat, who was of Levi,
\v 30 who was of Simeon, who was of Judas, who was of Joseph, who was of Jona, who was of Eliacim.
\v 31 who was of Melcha, who was of Menna, who was of Matthatha, who was of Nathan, who was of David, \f + \fr 3:31 \ft Melca\f*
\v 32 who was of Jesse, who was of Obed, who was of Booz, who was of Salmon, who was of Naasson,
\v 33 who was of Aminadab, who was of Aram, who was of Esron, who was of Phares, who was of Judas,
\v 34 who was of Jacob, who was of Isaac, who was of Abraham, who was of Thare, who was of Nachor,
\v 35 who was of Sarug, who was of Ragau, who was of Phaleg, who was of Heber, who was of Sale,
\v 36 who was of Cainan, who was of Arphaxad, who was of Sem, who was of Noe, who was of Lamech, \f + \fr 3:36 \ft Beza boldly wipeth out of this Gospel, these words, who was of Cainan: though all the Greek copies both of the old Testament & of the new, have the words with full consent. Whereby we learn the intolerable sauciness of the Calvinists, and their contempt of holy Scripture, that dare so deal with the very Gospel itself.\f*
\v 37 who was of Mathusale, who was of Henoch, who was of Jared, who was of Malaleel, who was of Cainan,
\v 38 who was of Henos, who was of Seth, who was of Adam, who was of God.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 \sc And Jesus\sc* full of the Holy Ghost, returned from Jordan, & was driven in the spirit into the desert.
\v 2 forty days, and was tempted of the devil. And he did eat nothing in those days; and when they were ended, he was an hungered. \f + \fr 4:2 \ft The Church's fast of 40 days (called Lent) cometh of this, & is an Apostolical Tradition. Clem. Constit. Apost. li. 5. c. 13. Hier. ep. ad Marcel. adv. erro. Montani. Leo ser. 6. et 9. de Quadrages.\f*
\v 3 And the devil said to him: If thou be the Son of God, say to this stone that it be made bread.
\v 4 And \sc Jesus\sc* made answer unto him: It is written, \add That not in bread alone shall man live, but in every word of God.\add*
\v 5 And the devil brought him into an high mountain, and shewed him all the kingdoms of the whole world in a moment of time;
\v 6 and he said to him: To thee will I give this whole power, and the glory of them; for to me they are delivered, and to whom I will, I do give them.
\v 7 Thou therefore if thou wilt adore before me, they shall all be thine.
\v 8 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering said to him: It is written, \add Thou shalt adore the Lord thy God & him only shalt thou \add* \add serve.\add* \f + \fr 4:8 \ft See the Annot. in S. Matthew c. 4, 11.\f* \f + \fr 4:8 \ft λατρεύσεις.\f*
\v 9 And he brought him into Jerusalem, & set him upon the pinnacle of the Temple; and he said to him: If thou be the Son of God, cast thyself from hence downward.
\v 10 For it is written, that \add He hath given his Angels charge of thee, that they preserve thee:\add* \f + \fr 4:10 \ft If the Devil himself allege Scripture against Christ, no marvel that Heretics do so against Christ's Church.\f*
\v 11 and that \add in their hands they shall bear thee up, lest perhaps thou knock thy foot against a stone.\add*
\v 12 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering said to him: It is said, \add Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God.\add*
\v 13 And all the tentation being ended, the devil departed from him until a time.
\v 14 And \sc Jesus\sc* returned in the force of the spirit into Galilee, and the fame went forth through the whole country of him. \f + \fr 4:14 \ft The third part: of Christ's manifesting himself by preaching and miracles, specially in Galilee.\f*
\v 15 And he taught in their Synagogues, and was magnified of all.
\v 16 And he came to Nazareth where he was brought up: and he entered according to his custom on the Sabboth day into the Synagogue; and he rose up to read. \f + \fr 4:16 \ft Our Saviour used to preach in their Synagogues.\f*
\v 17 And the book of Esay the Prophet was delivered unto him. And as he unfolded the book, he found the place where it was written:
\v 18 \add The Spirit of the Lord upon me, for which he anointed me, to evangelize unto the poor he sent me, to heal the contrite of heart,\add*
\v 19 \add to preach to the captives remission, and sight to the blind, to dismiss the bruised unto remission, to preach the acceptable year of the Lord, and the day of retribution.\add*
\v 20 And when he had folded the book, he rendered it to the minister, and sat down. And the eyes of all in the Synagogue were bent upon him.
\v 21 And he began to say unto them: That this day is fulfilled this scripture in your ears.
\v 22 And all gave testimony to him; and they marveled in the words of grace that proceeded from his mouth, and they said: Is not this Joseph's son? \f + \fr 4:22 \ft He had a marvelous grace, and an extraordinary force in moving the hearts of his hearers.\f*
\v 23 And he said to them: Certes you will say to me this similitude, \add Physician, cure thyself:\add* as great things as we have heard done in Capharnaum, do also here in thy country. \f + \fr 4:23 \ft The Gospel upon Monday in the 3. week of Lent.\f*
\v 24 And he said: Amen I say to you, that no Prophet is accepted in his own country.
\v 25 In truth I say to you, there were many widows in the days of Elias in Israel, when the Heaven was shut three years and six months, when there was a great famine made in the whole earth:
\v 26 And to none of them was Elias sent, but into Sarepta of Sidon, to a widow woman.
\v 27 And there were many lepers in Israel under Elisæus the Prophet; and none of them was made clean but Naaman the Syrian.
\v 28 And all in the Synagogue were filled with anger, hearing these things.
\v 29 And they rose, and cast him out of the city: and they brought him to the edge of the hill, where upon their city was built, that they might throw him down headlong.
\v 30 But he passing through the midst of them, went his way.
\v 31 And he went down into Capharnaum a city of Galilee; and there he taught them on the Sabboths.
\v 32 And they were astonished at his doctrine; because his talk was in power.
\v 33 And in the Synagogue there was a man having an unclean devil, and he cried out with a loud voice.
\v 34 Saying: Let be, what to us and thee \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth? Art thou come to destroy us? I know thee who thou art, \add the \sc Saint\sc* of God.\add*
\v 35 And \sc Jesus\sc* rebuked him, saying: Hold thy peace, & go out of him. And when the devil had thrown him into the midst, he went out of him, and hurted him nothing.
\v 36 And there came fear upon all, and they talked together one with another, saying: What word is this, that in power and virtue he commandeth the unclean spirits, and they go out?
\v 37 And the fame of him was published into every place of the country.
\v 38 And \sc Jesus\sc* rising up out of the Synagogue, entered into Simon's house. And Simon's wife's mother was holden with a great fever; and they besought him for her. \f + \fr 4:38 \ft The Gospel upon Thursday in the 3. week of Lent. And upon Imber Saturday in Whitsunweek. And in time of mortality. See Mar. 8, 22. in margin.\f*
\v 39 And standing over her, he commanded the fever, and it left her. And incontinent rising, she ministered to them.
\v 40 And when the sun was down, all that had diseased of sundry maladies, brought them to him. But he imposing hands upon every one, cured them.
\v 41 And devils went out from many, crying and saying: That thou art the Son of God. And rebuking them he suffered them not to speak, that they knew he was Christ.
\v 42 And when it was day, going forth he went into a desert place; & the multitudes sought him, and came even unto him; and they held him that he should not depart from them.
\v 43 To whom he said: That to other cities also must I evangelize the Kingdom of God; because therefore I was sent.
\v 44 And he was preaching in the Synagogues of Galilee.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass, when the multitudes pressed upon him to hear the word of God, and himself stood beside the lake of Genesareth. \f + \fr 5:1 \ft The Gospel upon the 4. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 2 And he saw two ships standing by the lake: and the fishers were gone down, and washed their nets.
\v 3 And he going up into one ship that was Simon's, desired him to bring it back a little from the land. And sitting, he taught the multitudes out of the ship.
\v 4 And as he ceased to speak, he said to Simon: Launch forth into the deep, and let loose your nets to make a draught.
\v 5 And Simon answering, said to him: Master, labouring all the night, we have taken nothing; but in thy word I will let loose the net.
\v 6 And when they had done this, they inclosed a very great multitude of fishes, and their net was broken.
\v 7 And they beckoned to their fellows that were in the other ship, that they should come and help them. And they came and filled both ships, so that they did sink.
\v 8 Which when Simon Peter did see, he fell down at \sc Jesus\sc*' knees, saying: Go forth from me, because I am a sinful man, O Lord.
\v 9 For he was wholly astonished and all that were with him, at the draught of fishes which they had taken.
\v 10 In like manner also James and John the sons of Zebedee, who were Simon's fellows. And \sc Jesus\sc* said to Simon: Fear not; from this time now, thou shalt be taking men.
\v 11 And having brought their ships to land, leaving all things they followed him.
\v 12 And it came to pass, when he was in one of the cities, & behold a man full of leprosy, and seeing \sc Jesus\sc*, and falling on his face, besought him saying: Lord, if thou wilt, thou canst make me clean.
\v 13 And stretching forth the hand, he touched him, saying: I will. Be thou made clean. And immediately the leprosy departed from him. \f + \fr 5:13 \ft Our Saviour often healeth by touching.\f*
\v 14 And he commanded him that he should tell nobody, but, Go, shew thyself to the Priest, and offer for thy cleansing as Moyses commanded, for a testimony to them.
\v 15 But the bruit of him went abroad the more, and great multitudes came together to hear, and to be cured of their infirmities.
\v 16 And he retired into the desert, and prayed.
\v 17 And it came to pass one day, and he sat teaching. And there were Pharisees sitting and Doctors of Law that were come out of every town of Galilee and Jewry and Jerusalem; and the virtue of our Lord was to heal them. \f + \fr 5:17 \ft The Gospel upon Imber Friday in Whitsunweek.\f*
\v 18 And behold men carrying in a bed a man that had the palsy: and they sought to bring him in, and to lay him before him.
\v 19 And not finding on which side they might bring him in for the multitude, they went up upon the roof, and through the tiles let him down with the bed into the midst, before \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 20 Whose faith when he saw, he said: Man, thy sins are forgiven thee.
\v 21 And the Scribes and Pharisees began to think, saying: Who is this that speaketh blasphemies? Who can forgive sins, but only God?
\v 22 And when \sc Jesus\sc* knew their cogitations, answering he said to them: What do you think in your hearts?
\v 23 Which is easier to say, Thy sins are forgiven thee, or to say, Arise, and walk?
\v 24 But that you may know that the Son of man hath power in earth to forgive sins (he said to the sick of the palsy) I say to thee, Arise, take up thy bed, and go into thy house.
\v 25 And forthwith rising up before them, he took that wherein he lay; and he went into his house, magnifying God.
\v 26 And all were astonished: and they magnified God. And they were replenished with fear, saying: That we have seen marvelous things today.
\v 27 And after these things he went forth, and saw a Publican called Levi, sitting at the Custom-house, and he said to him: Follow me. \f + \fr 5:27 \ft The Gospel upon S. Matthew's eve. Septemb. 20.\f*
\v 28 And leaving all things, he rose and followed him.
\v 29 And Levi made him a great feast in his house; and there was a great multitude of Publicans; and of others that were sitting at the table with them.
\v 30 And their Pharisees and Scribes murmured, saying to his disciples: Why do you eat and drink with Publicans and sinners?
\v 31 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering said to them: They that are whole, need not the Physician: but they that are ill at ease.
\v 32 I came not to call the just, but sinners to penance. \f + \fr 5:32 \ft Christ came not to call those, who presume of their own justice, and that count themselves to have no need of Christ.\f*
\v 33 But they said to him: Why do the disciples of John fast often, and make obsecrations, and of the Pharisees in like manner; but thine do eat and drink?
\v 34 To whom he said: Why, can you make the children of the bridegroom fast whiles the bridegroom is with them?
\v 35 But the days will come; and when the bridegroom shall be taken away from them, then they shall fast in those days.
\v 36 And he said a similitude also unto them: That no man putteth a piece from a new garment into an old garment; otherwise both he breaketh the new, and the piece from the new agreeth not with the old.
\v 37 And nobody putteth new wine into old bottles; otherwise the new wine will break the bottles, and itself will be shed, and the bottles will be lost.
\v 38 But new wine is to be put into new bottles: and both are preserved together.
\v 39 And no man drinking old, will new by and by, for he saith, The old is better.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass on the Sabboth second-first, when he passed through the corn, his Disciples did pluck the ears, & did eat rubbing them with their hands. \f + \fr 6:1 \ft S. Hierom (ep. 2. ad Nepotian.) writeth of himself, that being at Constantinople, he asked his master Gregory Nazianzene the famous Doctor, then Bishop there, what Sabboth this was. Who by his answer declared that it was very hard to tell; neither is it yet known to the best learned. Yet the Protestants are wont to say, All is very easy.\f*
\v 2 And certain of the Pharisees said to them: Why do you that which is not lawful on the Sabboths?
\v 3 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering them, said: Neither this have you read which David did, when himself was an hungered & they that were with him:
\v 4 how he entered into the house of God, and took the loaves of Proposition, and did eat, and gave to them that were with him, which it is not lawful to eat but only for Priests?
\v 5 And he said to them: That the Son of man is Lord of the Sabboth also.
\v 6 And it came to pass on another Sabboth also, that he entered into the Synagogue, and taught. And there was a man, and his right hand was withered.
\v 7 And the Scribes and Pharisees watched if he would cure on the Sabboth; that they might find how to accuse him.
\v 8 But he knew their cogitations; and he said to the man that had the withered hand: Arise, and stand forth into the midst. And rising he stood.
\v 9 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: I ask you, if it be lawful on the Sabboths to do well or ill; to save a soul or to destroy?
\v 10 And looking about upon them all, he said to the man: Stretch forth thy hand. And he stretched it forth; & his hand was restored.
\v 11 And they were replenished with madness; & they communed one with another what they might do to \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 12 And it came to pass in those days, he went forth into the mountain to pray, and he passed the whole night in the prayer of God. \f + \fr 6:12 \ft The Gospel upon S. Bartholomew's day. Aug. 24.\f*
\v 13 And when day was come, he called his Disciples; and he chose twelve of them (whom also he named \add Apostles\add* )
\v 14 Simon whom he surnamed Peter, and Andrew his brother, James and John, Philippe and Bartholomew,
\v 15 Matthew and Thomas, James of Alphæus and Simon that is called Zelotes,
\v 16 and Jude of James, and Judas Iscariote which was the traitor.
\v 17 And descending with them he stood in a plain place, and the multitude of his Disciples, and a very great company of people from all Jewry and Jerusalem, and the sea coast both of Tyre & Sidon, \f + \fr 6:17 \ft The Gospel upon SS. Fabian and Sebastian's day, Ian. 20. upon S. Dionyse day. Octo. 9. upon Allhallows' eve. And for many Martyrs.\f*
\v 18 Which were come to hear him, and to be healed of their maladies. And they that were vexed of unclean spirits, were cured.
\v 19 And all the multitude sought to touch him, because virtue went forth from him, and healed all.
\v 20 And he lifting up his eyes upon his Disciples, said: Blessed are ye poor: for yours is the Kingdom of God.
\v 21 Blessed are you that now are an hungered: because you shall be filled. Blessed are you that now do weep: because you shall laugh.
\v 22 Blessed shall you be when men shall hate you, and when they shall separate you, and upbraid you, and abandon your name as evil, for the Son of man's sake.
\v 23 Be glad in that day and rejoice: for behold, your reward is much in Heaven. For according to these things did their fathers to the Prophets.
\v 24 But woe to you that are rich: because you have your consolation.
\v 25 Woe to you that are filled: because you shall be hungry. Woe to you that now do laugh: because you shall mourn and weep.
\v 26 Woe, when all man shall bless you: For according to these things did their fathers to the false-Prophets.
\v 27 But to you I say that do hear: Love your enemies, do good to them that hate you.
\v 28 Bless them that curse you, and pray for them that calumniate you.
\v 29 And he that striketh thee on the cheek, offer also the other. And from him that taketh away from thee thy robe, prohibit not thy coat also.
\v 30 And to every one that asketh thee, give, and of him that taketh away the things that are thine, ask not again. \f + \fr 6:30 \ft That is, to every one justly asking. For that which is unjustly asked, may be justly denied. Aug. li. 1. c. 40. de Serm. Do. in monte.\f*
\v 31 And according as you will that men do to you, do you also to them in like manner.
\v 32 And if you love them that love you, what thank is to you? For sinners also love those that love them.
\v 33 And if ye do good to them that do you good: what thank is to you? For sinners also do this.
\v 34 And if ye lend to them of whom ye hope to receive; what thank is to you? For sinners also lend unto sinners, for to receive as much.
\v 35 But love ye your enemies; do good and lend, hoping for nothing thereby: and your reward shall be much, and you shall be the Sons of the Highest, because himself is beneficial upon the unkind and the evil.
\v 36 Be ye therefore merciful as also your Father is merciful. \f + \fr 6:36 \ft The Gospel upon the first Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 37 Judge not, & you shall not be judged. Condemn not, & you shall not be condemned. Forgive, and you shall be forgiven.
\v 38 Give, and there shall be given to you. Good measure & pressed down and shaken together and running over shall they give into your bosom. For with the same measure that you do mete, it shall be measured to you again.
\v 39 And he said to them a similitude also: Can the blind lead the blind? Do not both fall into the ditch?
\v 40 The Disciple is not above his Master: but every one shall be perfect, if he be as his Master.
\v 41 And why seest thou the mote in thy brother's eye: but the beam that is in thine own eye thou considerest not?
\v 42 Or how canst thou say to thy brother: Brother, let me cast out the mote out of thine eye: thyself not seeing the beam in thine own eye? Hypocrite, cast first the beam out of thine own eye; and then shalt thou see clearly to take forth the mote out of thy brother's eye.
\v 43 For there is no good tree that yieldeth evil fruits; nor evil tree, that yieldeth good fruit.
\v 44 For every tree is known by his fruit. For neither do they gather figs of thorns; neither of a bush do they gather the grape.
\v 45 The good man of the good treasure of his heart bringeth forth good; and the evil man of the ill treasure bringeth forth evil. For of the aboundance of the heart the mouth speaketh,
\v 46 And why call you me, Lord, Lord: and do not the things which I say?
\v 47 Every one that cometh to me, and heareth my words, and doeth them, I will shew you to whom he is like.
\v 48 He is like to a man building a house, that digged deep, and laid the foundation upon a rock. And when an inundation rose, the river beat against that house, and it could not move it; for it was founded upon a rock. \f + \fr 6:48 \ft He buildeth right & surely, that hath both faith and good works: he buildeth on sand, that trusteth to his faith or reading or knowledge of the scripture, and doth not work or live accordingly.\f*
\v 49 But he that heareth, and doeth not; is like to a man building his house upon the earth without a foundation: against the which the river did beat; and incontinent it fell, and the ruin of that house was great.
\c 7
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when he had fully said all his words into the ears of the people, he entered into Capharnaum.
\v 2 And the servant of a certain Centurion being sick, was ready to die: who was dear unto him.
\v 3 And when he had heard of \sc Jesus\sc*, he sent unto him the Ancients of the Jews, desiring him to come and heal his servant.
\v 4 But they being come to \sc Jesus\sc*, besought him earnestly, saying to him, That he is worthy that thou shouldest do this for him.
\v 5 For he loveth our Nation; and he hath built a Synagogue for us.
\v 6 And \sc Jesus\sc* went with them. And when he was now not far from the house, the Centurion sent his friends unto him, saying: Lord, trouble not thyself. For \add I am not worthy that thou shouldest enter under my roof.\add* \f + \fr 7:6 \ft See the Annotations upon S. Matth. c. 8, 8.\f*
\v 7 For the which cause neither did I think myself worthy to come to thee; but say the word, and my servant shall be made whole.
\v 8 For I also am a man subject to authority, having under me soldiers: and I say to this, go, and he goeth: and to another, come, and he cometh; and to my servant, do this, and he doeth it.
\v 9 Which \sc Jesus\sc* hearing, marveled; and turning to the multitudes that followed him he said: Amen I say to you, neither in Israel have I found so great faith.
\v 10 And they that were sent, being returned home, found the servant that had been sick, whole.
\v 11 And it came to pass, afterward he went into a city that is called Naim; and there went with him his Disciples and a very great multitude. \f + \fr 7:11 \ft The Gospel upon the 15. Sunday after Pentecost. And upon Thursday in the 4. week of Lent. And for S. Monica S. Augustin's mother. Maij. 4.\f*
\v 12 And when he came nigh to the gate of the city, behold a dead man was carried forth, the only son of his mother; and she was a widow: and a great multitude of the city with her.
\v 13 Whom when our Lord had seen, being moved with mercy upon her, he said to her: Weep not.
\v 14 And he came near and touched the coffin. And they that carried it stood still; and he said: Young man, I say to thee, arise.
\v 15 And he that was dead, sat up, and began to speak. And he gave him to his mother.
\v 16 And fear took them all; and they magnified God, saying, That a great Prophet is risen among us: and, that God hath visited his people.
\v 17 And this saying went forth into all Jewry of him, & into all the country about.
\v 18 And John's disciples shewed him of all these things.
\v 19 And John called two of his disciples, and sent them to \sc Jesus\sc*, saying: Art thou he that art to come; or expect we another?
\v 20 And when the men were come unto him, they said: John the Baptist hath sent us to thee, saying: Art thou he that art to come; or expect we another?
\v 21 (And the self same hour, he cured many of maladies, and hurts, and evil spirits: and to many blind he gave sight.) \f + \fr 7:21 \ft c ἐχαρίσατο.\f*
\v 22 And answering, he said to them: Go & report to John what you have heard and seen: That the blind see, the lame walk, the lepers are made clean, the deaf hear, the dead rise again,
\v 23 the poor are evangelized: and blessed is he whosoever shall not be scandalized in me. \f + \fr 7:23 \ft Pauperes evangelizantur, that is, to the poor the Gospel is preached, and they receive it.\f*
\v 24 And when John's messengers were departed, he began to say of John to the multitudes: What went you out into the desert to see? A reed moved with the wind?
\v 25 But what went you forth to see? A man clothed in soft garments? Behold they that are in costly apparel and delicacies, are in the house of kings. \f + \fr 7:25 \ft Mark this well concerning John's apparel and diet. See the Annotations upon S. Matth. c. 3, 4.\f*
\v 26 But what went you out for to see? A Prophet? Certes I say to you, and more than a Prophet.
\v 27 This is he of whom it is written: \add Behold I send mine Angel before thy face, which shall prepare thy way before thee.\add*
\v 28 For I say to you: A greater Prophet among the children of women than John the Baptist, there is no man. But he that is the lesser in the Kingdom of God, is greater than he.
\v 29 And all the people hearing and the Publicans, justified God, being baptized with John's baptism.
\v 30 But the Pharisees and the lawyers despised the counsel of God against themselves, being not baptized of him. \f + \fr 7:30 \ft As they that contemned John's Baptism, despised God's counsel & wisdom; so much more they that make no account of the Sacraments of the Church, despise God's counsel & ordinance touching their salvation, to their own damnation.\f*
\v 31 And our Lord said: Where unto then shall I liken the men of this generation, and whereunto are they like?
\v 32 They are like to children sitting in the market-place, and speaking one to another, and saying: We have piped to you, and you have not danced; we have lamented, and you have not wept.
\v 33 For John the Baptist came neither eating bread nor drinking wine; and you say: He hath a devil.
\v 34 The Son of man came eating and drinking; and you say: Behold a man that is a gourmander and a drinker of wine, a friend of Publicans and sinners.
\v 35 And wisdom is justified of all her children.
\v 36 And one of the Pharisees desired him to eat with him. And being entered into the house of the Pharisee, he sat down to meat. \f + \fr 7:36 \ft The Gospel upon S. Mary Magdalene's day Iul. 22. And upon Thursday in Passion Week. And upon Imber Friday in Sept.\f*
\v 37 And behold a woman that was in the city, a sinner, as she knew that he was set down in the Pharisee's house, she brought an alabaster box of ointment;
\v 38 and standing behind beside his feet, she began to water his feet with tears, & wiped them with the hairs of her head, and kissed his feet, & anointed them with the ointment. \f + \fr 7:38 \ft Aperfect pattern of true penance in this woman, who sought of Christ with open tears & other strange works of satisfaction and devotion, remission of her sins.\f*
\v 39 And the Pharisee that had bid him, seeing it, spake within himself, saying: This man if he were a Prophet, would know certes who and what manner of woman she is which toucheth him, that she is a sinner.
\v 40 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering said to him: Simon, I have somewhat to say unto thee. But he said: Master, say.
\v 41 Acertain creditor had two debters; one did owe five hundred pence, & the other fifty.
\v 42 They having not wherewith to pay, he forgave both. Whether therefore doth love him more?
\v 43 Simon answering said: I suppose that he to whom he forgave more. But he said to him: Thou hast judged rightly.
\v 44 And turning to the woman, he said unto Simon: Doest thou see this woman? I entered into thy house, water to my feet thou didst not give; but she with tears hath watered my feet, and with her hairs hath wiped them.
\v 45 Kiss thou gavest me not; but she since I came in, hath not ceased to kiss my feet.
\v 46 With oil thou didst not anoint my head; but she with ointment hath anointed my feet.
\v 47 For the which I say to thee: Many sins are forgiven her, because she hath loved much. But to whom less is forgiven, he loveth less. \f + \fr 7:47 \ft Not only faith (as yo may perceive) but love or charity obtaineth remission of sins.\f*
\v 48 And he said to her: Thy sins are forgiven thee.
\v 49 And they that sat together at the table began to say within themselves. Who is this that also forgiveth sins? \f + \fr 7:49 \ft As the Pharisees did always carp Christ for remission of sins in earth, so the Heretics reprehend his Church that remitteth sins by his authority.\f*
\v 50 And he said to the woman: Thy faith hath made thee safe, go in peace.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass afterward, and he made his journey by cities and towns preaching and evangelizing the Kingdom of God; and the Twelve with him,
\v 2 and some women that had been cured of wicked spirits and infirmities; Mary which is called Magdalene, out of whom seven devils were gone forth,
\v 3 And Joane the wife of Chusa Herod's procurator, and Susan, and many others that did minister unto him of their substance. \f + \fr 8:3 \ft c aliæ multæ\f*
\v 4 And when a very great multitude assembled and hastened out of the cities unto him, he said by a similitude. \f + \fr 8:4 \ft The Gospel upon the Sunday of Sexagesima.\f*
\v 5 The sower went forth to sow his seed. And whiles he soweth, some fell by the way side, and was trodden upon, and the fowls of the air did eat it.
\v 6 And other some fell upon the rock; and being shot up, it withered, because it had not moisture.
\v 7 And othersome fell among thorns, and the thorns growing up withal, choked it.
\v 8 And other some fell upon good ground; and being shot up, yielded fruit an hundred fold. Saying these things he cried: He that hath ears to hear, let him hear.
\v 9 And his Disciples asked him what this parable was.
\v 10 To whom he said: To you it is given to know the mystery of the Kingdom of God; but to the rest in parables, that seeing they may not see, and hearing may not understand. \f + \fr 8:10 \ft See the Annotations upon S. Matthew. c. 13, 14.\f*
\v 11 And the parable is this: The seed, is the word of God.
\v 12 And they besides the way, are those that hear, then the devil cometh, and taketh the word out of their heart, lest believing they be saved.
\v 13 For they upon the rock; such as when they hear, with joy receive the word: and these have no roots; because for a time they believe, and in time of tentation they revolt. \f + \fr 8:13 \ft Against the Heretics that say, faith once had cannot be lost, and that he which now hath not faith, never had.\f*
\v 14 And that which fell into thorns, are they that have heard, and going their ways, are choked with cares and riches and pleasures of this life, and render not fruit.
\v 15 And that upon good ground, are they which in a good and very good heart, hearing the word, do retain it, and yield fruit in patience.
\v 16 And no man lighting a candle doth cover it with a vessel, or put it under a bed; but setteth it upon a candlestick, that they that enter in, may see the light.
\v 17 For there is not any thing secret, that shall not be made manifest; nor hid, that shall not be known, & come abroad.
\v 18 See therefore how you hear. For he that hath, to him shall be given; and whosoever hath not, that also which he thinketh he hath, shall be taken away from him.
\v 19 And his mother and brethren came unto him; and they could not come at him for the multitude.
\v 20 And it was told him: Thy mother and thy brethren stand without, desirous to see thee.
\v 21 Who answering said to them: My mother and my brethren, are they that hear the word of God and do it. \f + \fr 8:21 \ft He did not here disdainfully speak of his mother, but teacheth that our Spiritual kindred is to be preferred before carnal cognation. Hilar. in 12. Mat.\f*
\v 22 And it came to pass one day; and he went up into a boat, and his Disciples, and he said to them: Let us strike over the lake. And they launched forth.
\v 23 And when they were sailing, he slept; and there fell a storm of wind into the lake, and they were filled, and were in danger. \f + \fr 8:23 \ft c complebantur.\f*
\v 24 And they came and raised him, saying: Master, we perish. But he rising, rebuked the wind and the tempest of water; and it ceased, and there was made a calm. \f + \fr 8:24 \ft See the Annotations upon S. Matthew c. 8, 24.\f*
\v 25 And he said to them: Where is your faith? Who fearing, marveled one to another, saying: Who is this (trow ye) that he commandeth both the winds and the sea, and they obey him?
\v 26 And they sailed to the country of the Gerasens which is over against Galilee.
\v 27 And when he was come forth to the land, there met him a certain man that had a devil now a very long time, and he did wear no cloths, neither did he tarry in house, but in the monuments.
\v 28 And as he saw \sc Jesus\sc*, he fell down before him; and crying out with a great voice, he said: What is to me & thee \sc Jesus\sc* Son of God most high? I beseech thee do not torment me.
\v 29 For he commanded the unclean spirit to go forth out of the man. For many times he caught him, and he was bound with chains, and kept with fetters; and breaking the bonds was driven of the devil into the deserts.
\v 30 And \sc Jesus\sc* asked him saying: What is thy name? But he said: Legion, because many devils were entered into him.
\v 31 And they besought him that he would not command them to go into the depth.
\v 32 And there was there a herd of many swine feeding on the mountain; & they desired him that he would permit them to enter into them. And he permitted them.
\v 33 The devils therefore went forth out of the man, and entered into the swine; and the herd with violence went headlong into the lake, and was stifled.
\v 34 Which when the swineherds saw done, they fled, and told into the city and into the towns.
\v 35 And they went forth to see that which was done; and they came to \sc Jesus\sc*, and found the man, out of whom the devils were gone forth, sitting at his feet, clothed, and well in his wits, and they were afraid.
\v 36 And they also that had seen, told them how he had been made whole from the legion.
\v 37 And all the multitude of the country of the Gerasens besought him to depart from them; for they were taken with great fear. And he going up into the boat, returned.
\v 38 And the man out of whom the devils were departed, desired him that he might be with him. But \sc Jesus\sc* dismissed him, saying:
\v 39 Return into thy house, and tell how great things God hath done to thee. And he went through the whole city, preaching how great things \sc Jesus\sc* had done to him.
\v 40 And it came to pass; when \sc Jesus\sc* was returned, the multitude received him. And all were expecting him.
\v 41 And behold there came a man whose name was Jairus, and he was Prince of the Synagogue: and he fell at the feet of \sc Jesus\sc*, desiring him that he would enter into his house,
\v 42 because he had an only daughter almost twelve years old, and she was a dying. And it chanced, whiles he went, he was thronged of the multitudes.
\v 43 And there was a certain woman in a flux of blood from twelve years past, which had bestowed all her substance upon Physicians, neither could she be cured of any: \f + \fr 8:43 \ft See the Annotations upon S. Matthew c. 9, 19.\f*
\v 44 she came behind him, and touched the hem of his garment; and forthwith the flux of her blood stinted,
\v 45 And \sc Jesus\sc* said: Who is it that touched me? And all denying, Peter said, and they that were with him: Master, the multitudes throng and press thee, and doest thou say, Who touched me? \f + \fr 8:45 \ft It is an evident sign of prerogative, that Peter only is named so often as chief of the company. Mar. 1, 36. Act. 5. 29. Luc. 9, 12. Mar. 16, 7. 1 Cor. 15, 5.\f*
\v 46 And \sc Jesus\sc* said: Somebody hath touched me; for I know that there is virtue proceeded from me.
\v 47 And the woman seeing, that she was not hid, came trembling, and fell down before his feet; and for what cause she had touched him, she shewed before all the people, and how forthwith she was made whole.
\v 48 But he said to her: Daughter, thy faith hath made thee safe, go thy way in peace.
\v 49 As he was speaking, there cometh one to the Prince of the Synagogue, saying to him, That thy daughter is dead, trouble him not.
\v 50 And \sc Jesus\sc* hearing this word, answered the father of the maid: Fear not; believe only, and she shall be safe. \f + \fr 8:50 \ft See the Annotations upon S. Mark. c. 5, 36.\f*
\v 51 And when he was come to the house, he permitted not any man to enter in with him, but Peter, and James, and John, and the father and mother of the maid.
\v 52 And all wept, and mourned for her. But he said: Weep not, the maid is not dead, but sleepeth.
\v 53 And they derided him, knowing that she was dead.
\v 54 But he holding her hand cried saying: Maid arise.
\v 55 And her spirit returned, and she rose incontinent. And he bade them give her to eat.
\v 56 And her parents were astonished, whom he commanded to tell no man that which was done.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* calling together the twelve Apostles, he gave them virtue and power over all devils, and to cure maladies. \f + \fr 9:1 \ft The Gospel upon Thursday in Whitsunweek.\f* \f + \fr 9:1 \ft To command Devils and diseases either of body or soul, is by nature proper to God only: but by God's gift, men also may have the same: even so to forgive sins.\f*
\v 2 And he sent them to preach the Kingdom of God; and to heal the sick.
\v 3 And he said to them: Take nothing for the way, neither rod, nor scrip, nor bread, nor money, neither have two coats.
\v 4 And into whatsoever house you enter, tarry there, and thence do not depart.
\v 5 And whosoever shall not receive you, going forth out of that city, shake off the dust also of your feet for a testimony upon them. \f + \fr 9:5 \ft Agreat fault to reject the true preachers, or not to admit them into house for needful harbour and sustenance.\f*
\v 6 And going forth they went a circuit from town to town evangelizing and curing every-where.
\v 7 And Herod the Tetrarch heard all things that were done by him; and he staggered because it was said of some, That John was risen from the dead.
\v 8 But of other some, That Elias hath appeared; and of others, that a Prophet one of the old ones was risen.
\v 9 And Herod said: John I have beheaded; but who is this of whom I hear such things? And he sought for to see him.
\v 10 And the Apostles being returned, reported to him whatsoever they did: and taking them he retired apart into a desert place, which belongeth to Beth-saida.
\v 11 Which the multitudes understanding, followed him & he received them, and spake to them of the Kingdom of God, and them that had need of cure he healed.
\v 12 And the day began to draw towards an end. And the Twelve coming near, said to him: Dismiss the multitudes, that going into towns and villages here about, they may have lodging, and find meats; because here we are in a desert place.
\v 13 And he said to them: Give you them to eat. But they said: We have no more but five loaves and two fishes; unless perhaps we should go & buy meats for all this multitude.
\v 14 And there were men almost five thousand. And he said to his Disciples: Make them sit down by companies fifty and fifty.
\v 15 And so they did. And they made all sit down.
\v 16 And taking the five loaves and the two fishes, he looked up unto Heaven, and blessed them; and he brake, and distributed to his Disciples, for to set before the multitudes. \f + \fr 9:16 \ft c εὐλόγησεν αὐτοὺς:\f* \f + \fr 9:16 \ft Here you see that he blessed the things, and not only gave thanks to God. See Annot. Marci. c. 8, 7.\f*
\v 17 And they did all eat, and had their fill. And there was taken up that which remained to them, twelve baskets of fragments. \f + \fr 9:17 \ft The miraculous providence of God toward such as follow Christ into deserts, prisons, banishment, or whithersoever.\f*
\v 18 And it came to pass; when he was alone praying, his Disciples also were with him; and he asked them saying: Whom do the multitudes say that I am?
\v 19 But they answered, and said: John the Baptist; and some, Elias; but some, that one of the Prophets before time, is risen.
\v 20 And he said to them: But whom say ye that I am? Simon Peter answering, said: The \sc Christ\sc* of God.
\v 21 But he rebuking them, commanded that they should tell this to no man,
\v 22 saying: That the Son of man must suffer many things, and be rejected of the Ancients and chief Priests and Scribes, and be killed, and the third day rise again.
\v 23 And he said to all: If any man will come after me, let him deny himself, and take up his cross daily, and follow me.
\v 24 For he that will save his life, shall lose it; for he that shall lose his life for my sake, shall save it.
\v 25 For what profit hath a man if he gain the whole world, and lose himself, and cast away himself?
\v 26 For he that shall be ashamed of me and of my words, him the Son of man shall be ashamed of, when he shall come in his majesty, and his Father's, and of the holy Angels.
\v 27 And I say to you assuredly: There be some standing here that shall not taste death, till they see the Kingdom of God.
\v 28 And it came to pass after these words almost eight days, and he took Peter and James and John, and went into a mountain to pray. \f + \fr 9:28 \ft The TRANSFIGURATION.\f*
\v 29 And whiles he prayed, the shape of his countenance was altered: and his raiment white and glistering.
\v 30 And behold two men talked with him. And they were Moyses and Elias,
\v 31 appearing in majesty. And they told his decease that he should accomplish in Jerusalem.
\v 32 But Peter and they that were with him, were heavy with sleep. And awaking, they saw his majesty, and the two men that stood with him.
\v 33 And it came to pass, when they departed from him, Peter said to \sc Jesus\sc*: Master, it is good for us to be here; and let us make three tabernacles, one for thee, and one for Moyses, and one for Elias: not knowing what he said.
\v 34 And as he spake these things, there came a cloud, and overshadowed them: and they feared, when they entered into the cloud.
\v 35 And a voice was made out of the cloud, saying: This is my beloved Son, hear him.
\v 36 And whiles the voice was made, \sc Jesus\sc* was found alone. And they held their peace, and told no man in those days any of these things which they had seen.
\v 37 And it came to pass the day following, when they came down from the mountain, there met him a great multitude.
\v 38 And behold a man of the multitude cried out, saying: Master, I beseech thee, look upon my son because he is mine only one.
\v 39 And lo, the spirit taketh him, and he suddenly cryeth, and he dasheth him, and teareth him that he foameth, and with much ado departeth renting him.
\v 40 And I desired thy Disciples to cast him out, and they could not.
\v 41 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering said: O faithless and perverse generation, how long shall I be with you and suffer you? Bring hither thy son. \f + \fr 9:41 \ft Incredulity hindereth the effect of Exorcisms, and other miraculous power given to the Church.\f*
\v 42 And when he came to him, the devil dashed, and tore him. And \sc Jesus\sc* rebuked the unclean Spirit, and healed the lad, and rendered him to his father.
\v 43 And all were astonished at the might of God; and all marveling at all things that he did, he said to his Disciples:
\v 44 Lay you in your hearts these words, for it shall come to pass that the Son of man shall be delivered into the hands of men.
\v 45 But they did not know this word, and it was covered before them, that they perceived it not. And they were afraid to ask him of this word.
\v 46 And there entered a cogitation into them, which of them should be greater. \f + \fr 9:46 \ft Desire of preeminence is an human infirmity often even among the good. Against which, Christ teacheth humility, but forbiddeth not Superiority.\f*
\v 47 But \sc Jesus\sc* seeing the cogitations of their heart, took a child and set him by him,
\v 48 and said to them, whosoever receiveth this child in my name, receiveth me, and whosoever receiveth me, receiveth him that sent me. For he that is the lesser among you all, he is the greater.
\v 49 And John answering said: Master, we saw a certain man casting out devils in thy name, and we prohibited him, because he followeth not with us.
\v 50 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Prohibit not. For he that is not against you, is for you. \f + \fr 9:50 \ft There be some that follow not Christ precisely in life and doctrine, of whom we may make our advantage to the propagation of Christ's honour and religion, when they do any thing for the advancement thereof, of what intention soever they do it. Philip. 1, 15.\f*
\v 51 And it came to pass, whiles the days of his assumption were accomplishing, and he fixed his face to go into Jerusalem.
\v 52 And he sent messengers before his face; and going they entered into a city of the Samaritans to prepare for him.
\v 53 And they received him not, because his face was to go to Jerusalem.
\v 54 And when his Disciples James and John had seen it, they said: Lord wilt thou we say that fire come down from Heaven and consume them? \f + \fr 9:54 \ft them as Elias also did?\f*
\v 55 And turning, he rebuked them, saying: You know not of what spirit you are.
\v 56 The Son of man came not to destroy souls, but to save. And they went into another town.
\v 57 And it came to pass as they walked in the way, a certain man said to him: I will follow thee whithersoever thou goest.
\v 58 \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: The foxes have holes, and the fowls of the air nests; but the Son of man hath not where to repose his head. \f + \fr 9:58 \ft This man would have followed him for temporal commodities, and therefore was not suffered.\f*
\v 59 But he said to another: Follow me. And he said: Lord, permit me first to go, and to bury my father.
\v 60 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Let the dead bury their dead; but go thou, set forth the Kingdom of God.
\v 61 And another said: I will follow thee Lord, but permit me first to take my leave of them that are at home.
\v 62 \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: No man putting his hand to the plough, and looking back, is apt for the Kingdom of God.
\c 10
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* after this our Lord designed also other seventy two: and he sent them two and two before his face into every city and place whither himself would come. \f + \fr 10:1 \ft The Gospel upon S. Mark's day. April. 25. and S. Luke's Octob. 18.\f* \f + \fr 10:1 \ft As the twelve Apostles did represent the higher degree of the Clergy, called Bishops: so these Seventy two bear the figure of the inferior Clergy, called Priests. Beda.\f*
\v 2 And he said to them: The harvest truly is much; but the workmen few. Desire therefore the Lord of the harvest, that he send workmen into his harvest.
\v 3 Go: Behold I send you as lambs among wolves.
\v 4 Carry not purse nor scrip, nor shoes; and salute nobody by the way.
\v 5 Into whatsoever house you enter, first say: Peace to this house.
\v 6 And if the son of peace be there, your peace shall rest upon him: but if not, it shall return to you.
\v 7 And in the same house tarry you, eating and drinking such things as they have. For the workman is worthy of his hire. Remove not from house to house.
\v 8 And into what city soever you enter, and they receive you, eat such things as are set before you;
\v 9 and cure the sick that are in it, and say to them: The Kingdom of God is come nigh upon you.
\v 10 And into whatsoever city you enter, and they receive you not, going forth into the streets thereof, say:
\v 11 The dust also of your city that cleaveth to us, we do wipe off against you. Yet this know ye that the Kingdom of God is at hand.
\v 12 Isay to you, it shall be more tolerable for Sodom in that day, than for that city. \f + \fr 10:12 \ft Differences of pains and damnation in Hell according to the differences of demerits. Aug. li. 5. c. 5. cont. Iulian.\f*
\v 13 Woe to thee Corozaim, woe to thee Beth-saida: for if in Tyre and Sidon had been wrought the miracles that have been wrought in you, they had done penance sitting in sack cloth and ashes long ago. \f + \fr 10:13 \ft True penance not only to lead a new life, but to punish that body by such things as here be recorded, for the ill life past.\f*
\v 14 But it shall be more tolerable for Tyre and Sidon in the judgement, than for you.
\v 15 And thou Capharnaum that art exalted unto Heaven: thou shalt be thrust down even unto hell.
\v 16 He that heareth you, heareth me; and he that despiseth you, despiseth me. And he that despiseth me, despiseth him that sent me. \f + \fr 10:16 \ft The Gospel for many Martyrs.\f* \f + \fr 10:16 \ft It is all one to despise Christ, and to despise his Priests and Ministers in the Catholic Church: to refuse his doctrine, & theirs.\f*
\v 17 And the Seventy-two returned with joy, saying: Lord, the devils also are subject to us in thy name.
\v 18 And he said to them: I saw Satan as a lightning fall from Heaven.
\v 19 Behold, I have given you power to tread upon serpents, and scorpions, and upon all the power of the enemy, and nothing shall hurt you.
\v 20 But yet rejoice not in this, that the spirits are subject unto you; but rejoice in this, that your names are written in Heaven.
\v 21 In that very hour he rejoiced in spirit, and said: I confess to thee O Father, Lord of Heaven and earth, because thou hast hid these things from the wise and prudent, and hast revealed them to little ones. Yea Father, for so hath it well pleased thee.
\v 22 All things are delivered to me of my Father. And no man knoweth who the Son is, but the Father; and who the Father is, but the Son, and to whom the Son will reveal.
\v 23 And turning to his Disciples, he said: Blessed are the eyes that see the things that you see.
\v 24 For I say to you, that many Prophets and kings desired to see the things that you see, and saw them not; and to hear the things that you hear, and heard them not. \f + \fr 10:24 \ft The Gospel upon the 12. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 25 And behold a certain lawyer stood up, tempting him and saying: Master, by doing of what thing shall I possess life everlasting?
\v 26 But he said to him: In the law what is written? How readest thou?
\v 27 He answering said: \add Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with thy whole heart, and with thy whole soul, and with all thy strength, and with all thy mind: and thy neighbour as thyself.\add*
\v 28 And he said to him: Thou hast answered right, this do and thou shalt live.
\v 29 But he desirous to justify himself, said to \sc Jesus\sc*: And who is my neighbour?
\v 30 And \sc Jesus\sc* taking it, said: A certain man went down from Jerusalem into Jericho, and fell among thieves, who also spoiled him, and giving him wounds went away leaving him half-dead.
\v 31 And it chanced that a certain Priest went down the same way; and seeing him, passed by.
\v 32 In like manner also a Levite, when he was near the place, and saw him, passed by.
\v 33 But a certain Samaritane going his journey, came near him; and seeing him, was moved with mercy.
\v 34 And going unto him, bound his wounds, pouring in oil and wine: and setting him upon his own beast, brought him into an inn, and took care of him.
\v 35 And the next day he took forth two pence, and gave to the host, and said: Have care of him; and whatsoever thou shalt supererogate, I at my return will repay thee. \f + \fr 10:35 \ft S. Augustine saith that the Apostle (1. Cor. 9.) according to this place did supererogate, that is, did more than he needed or was bound to do, when he might have required all duties for preaching the Gospel, but would not. li. de op. Monach. c. 5. Whereof it cometh, that the works which we do more than precept, be called works of Supererogation: &\f* \f + \fr 10:35 \ft Supererogaveris, προσδαπανήσῃς,\f*
\v 36 Which of these three in thy opinion was neighbour to him that fell among thieves?
\v 37 But he said: He that did mercy upon him. And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Go, and do thou in like manner.
\v 38 And it came to pass as they went, and he entered into a certain town; and a certain woman named Martha, received him into her house, \f + \fr 10:38 \ft b the Gospel upon the Assumption of our B. Lady. Aug. 15. And in the feast of S. Martha. Iulij. 29.\f*
\v 39 and she had a sister called Mary. Who sitting also at our Lord's feet, heard his word.
\v 40 But Martha was busy about much service. Who stood and said: Lord, hast thou no care that my sister hath left me alone to serve? Speak to her therefore, that she help me.
\v 41 And our Lord answering said to her: Martha, Martha, thou art careful, and art troubled about many things.
\v 42 But one thing is necessary, Mary hath chosen the best part which shall not be taken away from her.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass, when he was in a certain place praying, as he ceased, one of his Disciples said to him: Lord teach us to pray, as John also taught his Disciples.
\v 2 And he said to them: When you pray, say, \add \sc Father\sc*, sanctified be thy name. Thy Kingdom come,\add*
\v 3 \add Our daily bread give us this day,\add*
\v 4 \add and forgive us our sins, for because ourselves also do forgive every one that is in debt to us. And lead us not into temptation.\add*
\v 5 And he said to them: Which of you shall have a friend, and shall go to him at midnight, and shall say to him, Friend, lend me three loaves, \f + \fr 11:5 \ft The Gospel in Maioribus litanijs on S. Mark's day, and in the Rogation days. And in a votive Mass against the Pagans.\f*
\v 6 because a friend of mine is come out of his way to me, and I have not what to set before him:
\v 7 and he from within answering saith: Trouble me not, now the door is shut, and my children are with me in bed; I cannot rise and give thee.
\v 8 And if he shall persevere knocking, I say to you, although he will not rise and give him because he is his friend, yet for his importunity he will rise, and give him as many as he needeth.
\v 9 And I say to you, Ask, and it shall be given you: seek, and you shall find: knock, and it shall be opened to you. \f + \fr 11:9 \ft The Gospel in a votive Mass for remission of sins.\f*
\v 10 For every one that asketh, receiveth: and he that seeketh, findeth: and to him that knocketh, it shall be opened.
\v 11 And which of you if he ask his father bread, will he give him a stone? Or a fish, will he for a fish give him a serpent?
\v 12 Or if he ask an egg, will he reach him a scorpion?
\v 13 If you then being naught, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father from Heaven give the good spirit to them that ask him?
\v 14 And he was casting out a devil, and that was dumb. And when he had cast out the devil, the dumb spake: and the multitudes marveled.
\v 15 And certain of them said: In Beel-zebub the prince of devils he casteth out devils. \f + \fr 11:15 \ft The Gospel upon the 3. Sunday in Lent.\f*
\v 16 And other tempting, asked of him a sign from Heaven.
\v 17 But he seeing their cogitations, said to them: Every kingdom divided against itself, shall be made desolate, and house upon house, shall fall. \f + \fr 11:17 \ft c ὀῖκος ἐπὶ ὀῖκον\f*
\v 18 And if Satan also be divided against himself, how shall his kingdom stand? Because you say that in Beel-zebub I do cast out devils.
\v 19 And if I in Beel-zebub cast out devils: your children, in whom do they cast out? Therefore they shall be your judges.
\v 20 But if I in the finger of God do cast out devils; surely the Kingdom of God is come upon you. \f + \fr 11:20 \ft This finger, is the spirit of God, Mt. 12, 28.\f*
\v 21 When the strong armed keepeth his court, those things are in peace that he possesseth.
\v 22 But if a stronger than he come upon him and overcome him; he will take away his whole armour wherein he trusted, and will distribute his spoils.
\v 23 He that is not with me, is against me: and he that gathereth not with me, scattereth.
\v 24 When the unclean spirit shall depart out of a man, he wandereth through places without water, seeking rest. And not finding, he saith, I will return into my house whence I departed.
\v 25 And when he is come, he findeth it swept with a besom, and trimmed.
\v 26 Then he goeth and taketh seven other spirits worse than himself, and entering in they dwell there. And the last of that man be made worse than the first. \f + \fr 11:26 \ft c novissima fiunt\f*
\v 27 And it came to pass, when he said these things, a certain woman lifting up her voice out of the multitude said to him: Blessed is the womb that bare thee, and the paps that thou didst suck. \f + \fr 11:27 \ft b The Gospel in Dedicatione B. Mariæ ad Nives. Aug. 5. and upon Assumption eve, and in a Votive of our Lady between Candlemass and Easter, and between Pentecost and Advent.\f*
\v 28 But he said: Yea rather, blessed are they that hear the word of God, and keep it. \f + \fr 11:28 \ft The said mother of God, in that also was blessed that she was the temporal means & minister of the Incarnation, but much more blessed, in that she continued the perpetual keeper of his word. Beda. Aug. tract. 19. in Ioan.\f*
\v 29 And the multitudes running together, he began to say: This generation, is a wicked generation: it asketh a sign, and a sign shall not be given it but the sign of Jonas the Prophet.
\v 30 For as Jonas was a sign to the Ninivites; so shall the Son of man also be to this generation.
\v 31 The queen of the South shall rise in the judgement with the men of this generation, and shall condemn them: because she came from the ends of the earth to hear the wisdom of Salomon. And behold, more than Salomon here.
\v 32 The men of Ninivee shall rise in the judgement with this generation, and shall condemn it, because they did penance at the preaching of Jonas. And behold, more than Jonas here. \f + \fr 11:32 \ft μετενόησαν. Mark that the great penance of the Ninivites (Ionæ 3.) is here expressed by this Greek word. See Annot. Mat. 3, 2.\f*
\v 33 No man lighteth a candle, and putteth it in secret, neither under a bushel: but upon a candlestick, that they that go in may see the light. \f + \fr 11:33 \ft The Gospel upon S. Martin's day. Novem. 11. & for some other Confessors Bishops.\f*
\v 34 The candle of thy body is thine eye. If thine eye be simple, thy whole body shall be lightsome: but if it be naught, thy body also shall be darksome.
\v 35 See therefore that the light which is in thee, be not darkness.
\v 36 If then thy whole body be lightsome, having no part of darkness: it shall be lightsome wholly, and as a bright candle it shall lighten thee.
\v 37 And when he was speaking, a certain Pharisee desired him that he would dine with him. And he going in sat down to eat.
\v 38 And the Pharisee began to think within himself and to say: Why he was not washed before dinner.
\v 39 And our Lord said to him: Now you Pharisees do make clean that on the out side of the cup and of the platter; but that of yours which is within, is full of rapine and iniquity.
\v 40 Fools, did not he that made that on the out side, make that also that is on the inside?
\v 41 But yet that that remaineth, give alms, & behold all things are clean unto you. \f + \fr 11:41 \ft c Quod superest, τὰ ἐνόντα,\f*
\v 42 But woe to you Pharisees, because you tithe mint and rew and every herb: and pass over judgement and the charity of God. But these things you ought to have done, and not to omit those.
\v 43 Woe to you Pharisees, because you love the first chairs in the Synagogues, and salutations in the market place.
\v 44 Woe to you, because you are as monuments that appear not, and men walking over, are not ware.
\v 45 And one of the Lawyers answering saith to him: Master, in saying these things, thou speakest to our reproach also.
\v 46 But he said: Woe to you Lawyers also: because you load men with burdens which they cannot bear, and yourselves touch not the packs with one of your fingers.
\v 47 Woe to you that build the monuments of the Prophets: and your fathers did kill them. \f + \fr 11:47 \ft The Gospel for many Martyrs.\f* \f + \fr 11:47 \ft Not the building of the Prophets' monuments is condemned, but their imitation of their fathers that slew the Prophets. Ambros.\f*
\v 48 Surely you do testify that you consent to the works of your fathers: because they indeed did kill them, and you build their sepulchres.
\v 49 For this cause the wisdom also of God said, I will send to them Prophets and Apostles, and of them they will kill and persecute.
\v 50 That the blood of all the Prophets that was shed from the making of the world, may be required of this generation,
\v 51 from the blood of Abel unto the blood of Zacharie that was slain between the altar and the temple. Yea I say to you, it shall be required of this generation.
\v 52 Woe to you Lawyers, because you have taken away the key of knowledge: yourselves have not entered, & those that did enter you have prohibited.
\v 53 And when he said these things to them, the Pharisees & the Lawyers began vehemently to urge him, & to stop his mouth about many things,
\v 54 lying in wait for him, and seeking to catch something of his mouth, that they might accuse him.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when great multitudes stood about him, so that they trod one another, he began to say to his Disciples: Take good heed of the leaven of the Pharisees, which is hypocrisy. \f + \fr 12:1 \ft The Gospel upon SS. John and Paul's day, Iunij 26. And for many other Martyrs.\f*
\v 2 For nothing is hid, that shall not be revealed: nor secret, that shall not be known.
\v 3 For the things that you have said in darkness, shall be said in the light: and that which you have spoken into the ear in the chambers, shall be preached in the house-tops.
\v 4 And I say to you my friends, Be not afraid of them that kill the body, and after this have no more to do.
\v 5 But I will shew you whom ye shall fear: fear him who after he hath killed, hath power to cast into hell. Yea I say to you, fear him. \f + \fr 12:5 \ft The fear of Hell also is profitable: contrary to the protestants, teaching security of salvation, and that fear of Hell maketh men hypocrites.\f*
\v 6 Are not five sparrows sold for two farthings, and one of them is not forgotten before God?
\v 7 Yea the hairs also of your head are all numbered. Fear not therefore: you are more worth than many sparrows.
\v 8 And I say to you, Every one that confesseth me before men, the Son of man also will confess him before the Angels of God.
\v 9 But he that denieth me before men, shall be denied before the Angels of God.
\v 10 And every one that speaketh a word against the Son of man it shall be forgiven him: but he that shall blaspheme against the Holy Ghost, to him it shall not be forgiven.
\v 11 And when they shall bring you into the Synagogues and to Magistrates and Potestates, be not careful in what manner, or what you shall answer, or what you shall say.
\v 12 For the Holy Ghost shall teach you in the very hour what you must say.
\v 13 And one of the multitude said to him: Master, speak to my brother that he divide the inheritance with me.
\v 14 But he said to him: Man, who hath appointed me judge or divider over you?
\v 15 And he said to them: See and beware of all avarice: for not in any man's aboundance doth his life consist, of those things which he possesseth.
\v 16 And he spake a similitude to them, saying: A certain rich man's field yielded plenty of fruits.
\v 17 And he thought within himself, saying, What shall I do, because I have not whither to gather my fruits? \f + \fr 12:17 \ft Give it to the poor, that shouldst thou do, saith S. Basil.\f*
\v 18 And he said: This will I do, I will destroy my barns, and will make greater, and thither will I gather all things that are grown to me, and my goods.
\v 19 And I will say to my soul; Soul, thou hast much goods laid up for many years, take thy rest, eat, drink, make good cheer.
\v 20 But God said to him, Thou fool, this night they require thy soul of thee; and the things that thou hast provided, whose shall they be? \f + \fr 12:20 \ft Agoodly warning for all rich men.\f*
\v 21 So is he that layeth up treasure to himself, and is not rich to God-ward.
\v 22 And he said to his Disciples: Therefore I say to you, Be not careful for your life, what you shall eat; nor for your body, what you shall do on. \f + \fr 12:22 \ft He forbiddeth not competent providence, but too much carefulness. See Annot. upon S. Matth. c. 6, 25.\f*
\v 23 The life is more than the meat, and the body is more than the raiment.
\v 24 Consider the ravens, for they sow not, neither do they reap, which neither have storehouse nor barn, and God feedeth them. How much more are you of greater price than they?
\v 25 And which of you by caring can add to his stature one cubit?
\v 26 If then you be not able to do so much as the least thing, for the rest why are you careful?
\v 27 Consider the lilies how they grow: they labour not, neither do they spin. But I say to you, Neither Salomon in all his glory was arrayed as one of these.
\v 28 And if the grass that today is in the field, and tomorrow is cast into the oven, God so clotheth; how much more you, O ye of little faith?
\v 29 And you, do not seek what you shall eat, or what you shall drink: and be not lifted up on high. \f + \fr 12:29 \ft c μὴ μετεωρίζεσθε.\f*
\v 30 For all these things the Nations of the world do seek. But your Father knoweth that you have need of these things.
\v 31 But seek first the Kingdom of God, and all these things shall be given you besides.
\v 32 Fear not little flock, for it hath pleased your Father to give you a Kingdom. \f + \fr 12:32 \ft b The Gospel for S. Francis de Paula April. 2. S. Paulinus Jun. 22. S. Nicolas Tolentinas. Sept. 10. And for some other Confessors not Bishops.\f* \f + \fr 12:32 \ft It was little at the beginning, & is still in comparison of all the reprobate: but in itself very great, as in the parable of the great tree that grew of the little mustard seed. Mt. 13.\f*
\v 33 Sell the things that you possess, and give alms. Make to you purses that wear not, treasure that wasteth not, in Heaven: whither the thief approacheth not, neither doth the moth corrupt.
\v 34 For where your treasure is, there will your heart be also.
\v 35 Let your loins be girded, and candles burning in your hands, \f + \fr 12:35 \ft b The Gospel upon S. Silvester's day, Decemb. 31. S. Antony, Ian. 17. S. Antony of Padua, Iun. 13. S. Dominic. Augusti 4. And for some other Confessors not Bishops.\f* \f + \fr 12:35 \ft To gird our loins, is to keep chastity and continency. Gregor. ho. 13.\f*
\v 36 and you like to men expecting their Lord, when he shall return from the marriage: that when he doth come and knock, forthwith they may open unto him.
\v 37 Blessed are those servants, whom when the Lord cometh, he shall find watching. Amen I say to you, that he will gird himself, and make them sit down, and passing will minister unto them.
\v 38 And if he come in the second watch, and if in the third watch he come, and so find, blessed are those servants.
\v 39 And this know ye, that if the householder did know what hour the thief would come, he would watch verily, and would not suffer his house to be broken up.
\v 40 Be you also ready: for at what hour you think not, the Son of man will come.
\v 41 And Peter said to him: Lord, doest thou speak this parable to us, or likewise to all?
\v 42 And our Lord said: Who (thinkest thou) is a faithful steward and wise, whom the Lord appointeth over his family, to give them in season their measure of wheat?
\v 43 Blessed is that servant, whom when the Lord cometh, he shall find so doing.
\v 44 Verily I say to you, that over all things which he possesseth, he shall appoint him.
\v 45 But if that servant say in his heart, My Lord is long a coming; and shall begin to strike the servants and handmaids, and eat and drink, and be drunk:
\v 46 the Lord of that servant shall come in a day that he hopeth not, and at an hour that he knoweth not, and shall divide him, and shall appoint his portion with the infidels.
\v 47 And that servant that knew the will of his Lord, and prepared not himself, & did not according to his will, shall be beaten with many stripes.
\v 48 But he that knew not, and did things worthy of stripes, shall be beaten with few. And every one to whom much was given, much shall be required of him: and to whom they committed much, more will they demand of him.
\v 49 I came to cast fire on the earth; & what will I, but that it be kindled?
\v 50 But I have to be baptized with a baptism: and how am I straitened until it be dispatched?
\v 51 Think you that I came to give peace on the earth? No, I tell you, but separation. \f + \fr 12:51 \ft He meaneth the naughty peace that is between worldlings & sinners, the agreement that is in infidelity, in Heresy, or in any other wickedness. He came to break this peace. See Annot. Matth. c. 10, 34.\f*
\v 52 For there shall be from this time, five in one house divided: three against two, and two against three.
\v 53 There shall be divided, the father against the son, and the son against his father, the mother against the daughter, and the daughter against the mother, the mother in law against her daughter in law, and the daughter in law against her mother in law.
\v 54 And he said also to the multitudes, when you see a cloud rising from the west, by and by you say, A shower cometh, and so it cometh to pass:
\v 55 and when the south wind blowing, you say, That there will be heat: & it cometh to pass.
\v 56 Hypocrites, the face of the Heaven and of the earth you have skill to discern: but this time how do you not discern?
\v 57 And why of yourselves also judge you not that which is just?
\v 58 And when thou goest with thy adversary to the Prince, in the way endeavour to be delivered from him: lest perhaps he draw thee to the judge, and the judge deliver thee to the exactor, and the exactor cast thee into prison.
\v 59 Isay to thee, thou shalt not go out thence, until thou pay the very last mite.
\c 13
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* there were certain present at that very time telling him of the Galilæans, whose blood Pilate mingled with their sacrifices.
\v 2 And he answering said to them: Think you that these Galilæans were sinners more than all the Galilæans, that they suffered such things?
\v 3 No, I say to you: but unless you have penance, you shall all likewise perish. \f + \fr 13:3 \ft Or as it is uttered in other places, do penance, μετανοῆτε. the which in the new Testament signifieth perfect repentance. See Annotations Mat. 3, 2. 11, 21.\f* \f + \fr 13:3 \ft Nisi poenitentiam habueritis,\f*
\v 4 As those eighteen upon whom the tower fell in Siloe, and slew them: think you that they also were debters above all the men that dwell in Jerusalem?
\v 5 No, I say to you: but if you have not penance you shall all likewise perish.
\v 6 And he said this similitude: A certain man had a figtree planted in his vineyard, and he came seeking for fruit on it, and found not. \f + \fr 13:6 \ft The Gospel on the Imber Saturday in Sept.\f* \f + \fr 13:6 \ft The figtree with only leaves & no fruit, is the Jews' synagogue, & every other people or person which hath faith and fair words, and no good works.\f*
\v 7 And he said to the dresser of the vineyard, Lo it is three years since I come seeking for fruit upon this figtree, and I find not. Cut it down therefore; whereto doth it also occupy the ground?
\v 8 But he answering said to him: Lord, let it alone this year also, until I dig about it, and dung it.
\v 9 And if happily it yield fruit: but if not, hereafter thou shalt cut it down.
\v 10 And he was teaching in their Synagogue on the Sabboths.
\v 11 And behold a woman that had a spirit of infirmity eighteen years: and she was crooked, neither could she look upward at all.
\v 12 Whom when \sc Jesus\sc* saw, he called her unto him, and said to her: Woman, thou art delivered from thy infirmity.
\v 13 And he imposed hands upon her, and forthwith she was made straight and glorified God.
\v 14 And the Archsynagogue answering (because he had indignation that \sc Jesus\sc* had cured on the Sabboth) said to the multitude: Six days there are wherein you ought to work. In them therefore come, and be cured; and not in the Sabboth day.
\v 15 And our Lord answering to him, said: Hypocrite, doth not every one of you upon the Sabboth loose his ox or his ass from the manger, and leadeth them to water?
\v 16 But this daughter of Abraham whom Satan hath bound, lo, these eighteen years, ought not she to be loosed from this bond on the Sabboth day?
\v 17 And when he said these things, all his adversaries were ashamed: and all the people rejoiced in all things that were gloriously done of him.
\v 18 He said therefore: Whereunto is the Kingdom of God like, and whereunto shall I esteem it like?
\v 19 It is like to a mustard seed, which a man took and cast into his garden and it grew, and became a great tree, & the fowls of the air rested in the boughs thereof. \f + \fr 13:19 \ft See Annota. Matth. 13, 31.\f*
\v 20 And again he said: Like to what shall I esteem the Kingdom of God?
\v 21 It is like to leaven, which a woman took and hid in three measures of meal, till the whole was leavened.
\v 22 And he went by the cities and towns teaching, and making his journey unto Jerusalem.
\v 23 And a certain man said to him: Lord, be they few that are saved? But he said to them:
\v 24 Strive to enter by the narrow gate: because many, I say to you, shall seek to enter, and shall not be able. \f + \fr 13:24 \ft Christians in their lives must seek the strait way, but in religion the ancient common way.\f*
\v 25 But when the good-man of the house shall enter in, and shut the door, and you shall begin to stand without, and knock at the door, saying, Lord open to us: and he answering shall say to you, I know you not whence you are:
\v 26 then you shall begin to say: We did eat before thee and drink, and in our streets didst thou teach.
\v 27 And he shall say to you, I know you not whence you are, depart from me all ye workers of iniquity.
\v 28 There shall be weeping and gnashing of teeth: when you shall see Abraham and Isaac and Jacob, and all the Prophets in the Kingdom of God, and you to be thrust out.
\v 29 And there shall come from the East and West & the North and the South; and shall sit down in the Kingdom of God.
\v 30 And behold, they are last that shall be first, and they be first that shall be last. \f + \fr 13:30 \ft The Gentiles coming into God's favour later, are preferred before the Jews which were first.\f*
\v 31 The same day there came certain of the Pharisees, saying to him: Depart and get thee hence, because Herod will kill thee.
\v 32 And he said to them: Go, and tell that fox, Behold I cast out devils, and perfit cures this day and tomorrow, and the third day I am consummate.
\v 33 But yet I must walk this day and tomorrow and the day following, because it cannot be that a Prophet perish out of Jerusalem. \f + \fr 13:33 \ft c Non capit ὀυκ ἐνδέχεται\f*
\v 34 Jerusalem, Jerusalem which killest the Prophets, and stonest them that are sent to thee, how often would I gather thy children as the bird doth her brood under her wings, and thou wouldest not? \f + \fr 13:34 \ft The Jews lost their preeminence, by their own free will, & not by God's causing: who ceased not to call and cry upon them, and they would not hear. Whereby free will is plainly proved.\f*
\v 35 Behold your house shall be left desert to you. And I say to you, that you shall not see me till it come when you shall say: Blessed is he that cometh in the name of our Lord.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass when \sc Jesus\sc* entered into the house of a certain Prince of the Pharisees upon the Sabboth to eat bread, and they watched him. \f + \fr 14:1 \ft The Gospel upon the 16. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 2 And behold there was a certain man before him that had the dropsy.
\v 3 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering, spake to the Lawyers and Pharisees, saying: Is it Lawful to cure on the Sabboth?
\v 4 But they held their peace. But he taking him, healed him, and sent him away.
\v 5 And answering them he said: Which of you shall have an ass or an ox fallen into a pit; and will not incontinent draw him out on the Sabboth day?
\v 6 And they could not answer him to these things.
\v 7 And he spake to them also that were invited a parable, marking how they chose the first seats at the table, saying to them:
\v 8 When thou art invited to a marriage, sit not down in the first place, lest perhaps a more honourable than thou be invited of him;
\v 9 and he that bade thee and him, come and say to thee, Give this man place: and then thou begin with shame to take the last place.
\v 10 But when thou art bidden, go, sit down in the lowest place: that when he that invited thee cometh, he may say to thee, Friend sit up higher: then shalt thou have glory before them that sit at table with thee.
\v 11 because every one that exalteth himself, shall be humbled: and he that humbleth himself, shall be exalted.
\v 12 And he said to him also that had invited him: When thou makest a dinner or a supper, call not thy friends, nor thy brethren, nor kinsmen, nor thy neighbours that are rich: lest perhaps they also invite thee again, and recompence be made to thee.
\v 13 But when thou makest a feast, call the poor, feeble, lame, and blind,
\v 14 and thou shalt be blessed, because they have not to recompence thee: for recompence shall be made thee in the resurrection of the just. \f + \fr 14:14 \ft Reward for charitable deeds, and that they may be done for reward: Against our Adversaries.\f*
\v 15 When one of them that sat at the table with him, had heard these things, he said to him: Blessed is he that shall eat bread in the Kingdom of God.
\v 16 But he said to him: A certain man made a great supper, and called many. \f + \fr 14:16 \ft The Gospel upon the 2. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 17 And he sent his servant at the hour of supper to say to the invited, that they should come, because now all things are ready.
\v 18 And they began all at once to make excuse. The first said to him, I have bought a farm, and I must needs go forth and see it; I pray thee hold me excused. \f + \fr 14:18 \ft Worldliness, wealth, and voluptuousness, are the things that specially hinder men from God.\f*
\v 19 And another said, I have bought five yoke of oxen, and I go to prove them; I pray thee, hold me excused.
\v 20 And another said, I have married a wife, and therefore I cannot come.
\v 21 And the servant returning told these things to his Lord. Then the Master of the house being angry, said to his servant: Go forth quickly into the streets and lanes of the city, and the poor and feeble and blind and lame bring in hither.
\v 22 And the servant said: Lord, it is done as thou didst command, and yet there is place.
\v 23 And the Lord said to the servant: Go forth into the ways and hedges; and compel them to enter, that my house may be filled.
\v 24 But I say to you, that none of those men that were called, shall taste my supper.
\v 25 And great multitudes went with him; and turning, he said to them: \f + \fr 14:25 \ft The Gospel for some Martyrs Bishops. And for S. Basil. Ian. 14.\f*
\v 26 If any man come to me and hateth not his father and mother, and wife and children, and brethren and sisters, yea and his own life besides; he cannot be my disciple. \f + \fr 14:26 \ft No creature so dear unto us, which we must not hate or forsake, if it hinder us, and in that respect that it hindereth us from Christ, or his Church, & our Salvation.\f*
\v 27 And he that doth not bear his cross and come after me; cannot be my Disciple.
\v 28 For, which of you minding to build a tower, doth not first sit down and reckon the charges that are necessary, whether he have to finish it:
\v 29 lest, after that he hath laid the foundation, and is not able to finish it, all that see it, begin to mock him,
\v 30 saying, That this man began to build, and he could not finish it?
\v 31 Or what king about to go to make war against another king, doth not first sit down and think whether he be able with ten thousands to meet him that with twenty thousands cometh against him?
\v 32 Otherwise whiles he is yet far off, sending a legacy he asketh those things that belong to peace.
\v 33 So therefore every one of you that doth not renounce all that he possesseth, cannot be my disciple. \f + \fr 14:33 \ft He that is a right Christian man, must make his account that if he be put to it (as he often may be in times of persecution) he must renounce all that ever he hath, rather than forsake the Catholic faith.\f*
\v 34 Salt is good. But if the salt leese his virtue, wherewith shall it be seasoned?
\v 35 It is profitable neither for the ground, nor for the dunghill, but it shall be cast forth. He that hath ears to hear, let him hear.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* there approached Publicans and sinners unto him for to hear him. \f + \fr 15:1 \ft The Gospel upon the 3. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 2 And the Pharisees and the Scribes murmured saying: That this man receiveth sinners, and eateth with them.
\v 3 And he spake to them this parable, saying:
\v 4 What man of you having an hundred sheep: and if he hath lost one of them, doth he not leave the ninety nine in the desert, and goeth after that which was lost until he find it? \f + \fr 15:4 \ft This man, is our Saviour Christ: whose care & travail in searching & reducing sinners to repentance, all spiritual men specially should follow.\f*
\v 5 And when he hath found it, layeth it upon his shoulders rejoicing:
\v 6 and coming home calleth together his friends and neighbours, saying to them: Rejoice with me, because I have found my sheep that was lost?
\v 7 Isay to you, that even so there shall be joy in Heaven upon one sinner that doth penance, than upon ninety nine just that need not penance.
\v 8 Or what woman having ten groats: if she leese one groat, doth she not light a candle, and sweep the house, and seek diligently, until she find? \f + \fr 15:8 \ft This woman is the Catholic Church, who also continually seeketh her lost children.\f*
\v 9 And when she hath found, calleth together her friends and neighbours, saying: Rejoice with me, because I have found the groat which I had lost?
\v 10 So I say to you, there shall be joy before the Angels of God upon one sinner that doth penance.
\v 11 And he said: A certain man had two sons; \f + \fr 15:11 \ft The Gospel upon Saturday in the 2. week of Lent.\f*
\v 12 and the younger of them said to his father: Father, give me the portion of substance that belongeth to me. And he divided unto them the substance.
\v 13 And not many days after the younger son gathering all his things together went from home into a far country: and there he wasted his substance, living riotously. \f + \fr 15:13 \ft The prodigal son, is a parable, both of the Gentiles' conversion, & also of every dissolute sinner penitently returning to God.\f*
\v 14 And after he had spent all, there fell a sore famine in that country, and he began to be in need.
\v 15 And he went, and cleaved to one of the citizens of that country. And he sent him into his farm to feed swine.
\v 16 And he would fain have filled his belly of the husks that the swine did eat; and nobody gave unto him.
\v 17 And returning to himself he said: How many of my father's hirelings have aboundance of bread, and I here perish for famine?
\v 18 I will arise, and will go to my father, and say to him: Father, I have sinned against Heaven and before thee:
\v 19 I am not now worthy to be called thy son: make me as one of thy hirelings.
\v 20 And rising up he came to his father. And when he was yet far off, his father saw him, and was moved with mercy, and running to him fell upon his neck, and kissed him. \f + \fr 15:20 \ft God's wonderful and tender mercy toward penitent sinners.\f*
\v 21 And his son said to him: Father, I have sinned against Heaven & before thee, I am not now worthy to be called thy son.
\v 22 And the father said to his servants: Quickly bring forth the first stole, and do it on him, and put a ring upon his hand, and shoes upon his feet:
\v 23 and bring the fatted calf, and kill it, and let us eat, and make merry:
\v 24 because this my son was dead, and is revived: was lost, and is found. And they began to make merry.
\v 25 But his elder son was in the field, and when he came and drew nigh to the house, he heard music and dancing:
\v 26 and he called one of the servants, and asked what these things should be.
\v 27 And he said to him: Thy brother is come, and thy father hath killed the fatted calf, because he hath received him safe.
\v 28 But he had indignation, and would not go in. His father therefore going forth began to desire him.
\v 29 But he answering said to his father: Behold, so many years do I serve thee, and I never transgressed thy commandment, and thou didst never give me a kid to make merry with my friends:
\v 30 but after that this thy son, that hath devoured his substance with whores, is come, thou hast killed for him the fatted calf.
\v 31 But he said to him: Son, thou art always with me, and all my things are thine.
\v 32 But it behoved us to make merry and be glad because this thy brother was dead, and is revived, was lost, and is found.
\c 16
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* he said also to his Disciples: There was a certain rich man that had a bailiff: & he was ill reported of unto him, as he that had wasted his goods. \f + \fr 16:1 \ft The Gospel upon the 8. Sunday after Pentecost.\f* \f + \fr 16:1 \ft c ὀικονόμον.\f*
\v 2 And he called him, and said to him: What hear I this of thee? Render account of thy bailiffship: for now thou canst no more be bailiff. \f + \fr 16:2 \ft c ὀικονομίας.\f*
\v 3 And the bailiff said within himself: What shall I do, because my lord taketh away from me the bailiffship? Dig I am not able, to beg I am ashamed.
\v 4 I know what I will do, that when I shall be removed from the bailiffship, they may receive me into their houses.
\v 5 Therefore calling together every one of his lord's debters, he said to the first: How much doest thou owe my lord?
\v 6 But he saith: An hundred pipes of oil. And he said to him: Take thy bill and sit down, quickly write fifty.
\v 7 After that he said to another: But thou, how much doest thou owe? Who said: An hundreth quarters of wheat. He said to him: Take thy bill, and write eighty.
\v 8 And the lord praised the bailiff of iniquity, because he had done wisely: for the children of this world, are wiser than the children of light in their generation.
\v 9 And I say to you: Make unto you friends of the mammon of iniquity that when you fail, they may receive you into the eternal tabernacles. \f + \fr 16:9 \ft Mammon (saith S. Hierom q. 6. ad Algas.) in the Syriac tongue signifieth riches. Mammon of iniquity, because they are often ill gotten, or ill bestowed, or occasion of evil, or at the least worldly & false & not the true heavenly riches.\f*
\v 10 He that is faithful in the least, is faithful in the greater also: and he that is unjust in little, is unjust in the greater also.
\v 11 If then you have not been faithful in the unjust mammon, with that which is the true who may credit you?
\v 12 And if you have not been faithful in other men's, that which is yours, who will give you?
\v 13 No servant can serve two masters; for either he shall hate the one, and love the other; or cleave to one, and contemn the other. You cannot serve God and mammon.
\v 14 And the Pharisees which were covetous, heard all these things: and they derided him.
\v 15 And he said to them: You are they that justify yourselves before men, but God knoweth your hearts, because that which is high to men, is abomination before God.
\v 16 The Law and the Prophets, unto John. From that time the Kingdom of God is evangelized, and every one doth force toward it.
\v 17 And it is easier for Heaven and earth to pass, than one tittle of the law to fall.
\v 18 Every one that dismisseth his wife, and marrieth another, committeth adultery: and he that marrieth her that is dismissed from her husband, committeth adultery.
\v 19 There was a certain rich man, & he was clothed with purple and silk: and he fared every day magnifically. \f + \fr 16:19 \ft The Gospel upon Thursday in the 2. week of Lent.\f*
\v 20 And there was a certain beggar called Lazarus, that lay at his gate, full of sores:
\v 21 desiring to be filled of the crumbs, that fell from the rich man's table, but the dogs also came, and licked his sores. \f + \fr 16:21 \ft * and no man did give him.\f*
\v 22 And it came to pass that the beggar died, and was carried of the Angels into Abraham's bosom. And the rich man also died: and he was buried in hell.
\v 23 And lifting up his eyes, when he was in torments, he saw Abraham a far off, and Lazarus in his bosom: \f + \fr 16:23 \ft Lazarus in Abraham's bosom, and rest: but both in hell, and not in the kingdom of heaven before Christ. Hiero. ep. 3. Epitaph. Nepot.\f*
\v 24 and he crying said: Father Abraham, have mercy on me, and send Lazarus that he may dip the tip of his finger into water for to cool my tongue, because I am tormented in this flame.
\v 25 And Abraham said to him: Son, remember that thou didst receive good things in thy life time, and Lazarus likewise evil: but now he is comforted, and thou art tormented. \f + \fr 16:25 \ft To be in continual pleasures, ease, wealth, peace, and prosperity in this world, is perilous, & a sign of pains in the next. S. Hiero.\f*
\v 26 And beside all these things, between us and you there is fixed a great chaos: that they which will pass from hence to you, may not, neither go from thence hither. \f + \fr 16:26 \ft c χάσμα. a horrible distance.\f*
\v 27 And he said: Then, father, I beseech thee that thou wouldest send him unto my father's house, for I have five brethren,
\v 28 for to testify unto them, lest they also come into this place of torments.
\v 29 And Abraham said to him: They have Moyses and the Prophets: let them hear them. \f + \fr 16:29 \ft Abraham had knowledge of things in earth which were not in his time; as that they had Moyses' and the Prophets' books which he never saw. August. de cura pro mor. c. 14.\f*
\v 30 But he said: No, father Abraham, but if some man shall go from the dead to them, they will do penance.
\v 31 And he said to him: If they hear not Moyses and the Prophets, neither if one shall rise again from the dead, will they believe.
\c 17
\p
\v 1 And he said to his Disciples: It is impossible that scandals should not come: but woe to him by whom they come. \f + \fr 17:1 \ft Not of mere necessity, for then it were no fault: but presupposing the great wickedness of men, it is impossible but there shall be scandals, & therefore it followeth, Woe to him by whom they come.\f*
\v 2 It is more profitable for him, if a mill-stone be put about his neck, and he be cast into the sea, than that he scandalize one of these little ones.
\v 3 Look well to yourselves. If thy brother sin against thee, rebuke him: and if he do penance, forgive him.
\v 4 And if he sin against thee seven times in a day, and seven times in a day be converted unto thee, saying, It repenteth me, forgive him.
\v 5 And the Apostles said to our Lord: Increase faith in us.
\v 6 And our Lord said: If you had faith like to a mustard-seed, you might say to this mulberry tree, be thou rooted up, and be transplanted into the sea: and it would obey you.
\v 7 And which of you having a servant plowing or keeping cattle, that will say to him returning out of the field: Pass quickly, sit down:
\v 8 and saith not to him: Make ready supper, and gird thyself, and serve me whiles I eat and drink, and afterward thou shalt eat and drink?
\v 9 Doth he give that servant thanks, for doing the things which he commanded him?
\v 10 Itrow not: So you also, when you shall have done all things that are commanded you, say: We are unprofitable servants; we have done that which we ought to do.
\v 11 And it came to pass, as he went unto Jerusalem, he passed through the midst of Samaria and Galilee. \f + \fr 17:11 \ft The fourth part of this Gospel. The coming of Christ into Jewry, towards his Passion.\f* \f + \fr 17:11 \ft The Gospel upon the 13. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 12 And when he entered into a certain town, there met him ten men that were lepers, who stood a far off;
\v 13 and they lifted up their voice, saying: \sc Jesus\sc* Master, have mercy on us.
\v 14 Whom as he saw, he said: Go, shew yourselves to the Priests. And it came to pass, as they went, they were made clean.
\v 15 And one of them as he saw that he was made clean, went back with a loud voice magnifying God,
\v 16 and he fell on his face before his feet, giving thanks: and this was a Samaritane.
\v 17 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering said: Were not ten made clean? and where are the nine?
\v 18 There was not found that returned, and gave glory to God, but this stranger.
\v 19 And he said to him: Arise, go thy ways; because thy faith hath made thee safe. \f + \fr 17:19 \ft And yet we see here it was not only faith, but also his thankfulness & returning to give glory to God.\f*
\v 20 And being asked of the Pharisees: when cometh the Kingdom of God? he answered them and said: The Kingdom of God cometh not with observation:
\v 21 neither shall they say: Lo here, or lo there. For lo the Kingdom of God is within you. \f + \fr 17:21 \ft Whilst they ask and look for a temporal kingdom in pomp and glory, lo their King & Messias was now among them: whose spiritual kingdom is within all the faithful that have dominion over sin.\f*
\v 22 And he said to his Disciples: The days will come when you shall desire to see one day of the Son of man; and you shall not see.
\v 23 And they will say to you: Lo here and lo there. Go not, neither do ye follow after. \f + \fr 17:23 \ft No man must run out of the Church after Schismatics to hear them preach Christ in corners, Christ's doctrine being open in all the world. See annot. Mt. 24, 23.\f*
\v 24 For even as the lightning that lighteneth from under Heaven, unto those parts that are under Heaven, shineth: so shall the Son of man be in his day.
\v 25 But first he must suffer many things and be rejected of this generation.
\v 26 And as it came to pass in the days of Noe, so shall it be also in the days of the Son of man.
\v 27 They did eat and drink, they did marry wives and were given to marriage even until the day that Noe entered into the ark: and the flood came, and destroyed them all.
\v 28 Likewise as it came to pass in the days of Lot: They did eat and drink, bought and sold, planted, and builded:
\v 29 and in the day that Lot went out from Sodom, it rained fire & brimstone from Heaven, & destroyed them all:
\v 30 according to these things it shall be in the day that the Son of man shall be revealed.
\v 31 In that hour he that shall be in the house-top, and his vessels in the house, let him not go down to take them up: & he that is in the field, in like manner let him not return back.
\v 32 Be mindful of Lot's wife.
\v 33 Whosoever seeketh to save his life, shall lose it: and Whosoever doth lose the same, shall quicken it.
\v 34 Isay to you, in that night there shall be two in one bed: the one shall be taken, and the other shall be left:
\v 35 two women shall be grinding together: the one shall be taken, and the other shall be left. two in the field: the one shall be taken, and the other shall be left.
\v 36 They answering say to him: Where Lord?
\v 37 Who said to them: Wheresoever the body shall be, thither will the eagles also be gathered together.
\c 18
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* he spake also a parable to them that it behoveth always to pray, & not to be weary, \f + \fr 18:1 \ft We should pray always by faith, hope, and charity, and by working the things that be acceptable to God: though special times of vocal prayers in the Canonical hours be assigned for the stirring of us up to God through external signs of devotion.\f*
\v 2 saying: There was a certain judge in a certain city, which feared not God, and of man made no account.
\v 3 And there was a certain widow in that city, and she came to him, saying: Revenge me of mine adversary.
\v 4 And he would not of a long time. But afterward he said within himself: Although I fear not God, nor make account of man,
\v 5 yet because this widow is importune upon me, I will revenge her, lest at the last she come and defame me.
\v 6 And our Lord said: Hear what the judge of iniquity sayeth.
\v 7 And will not God revenge his elect that cry to him day and night: and will he have patience in them?
\v 8 Isay to you that he will quickly revenge them. But yet the Son of man coming, shall he find trow you, faith in the earth?
\v 9 And he said also to certain that trusted in themselves as just, and despised others, this parable: \f + \fr 18:9 \ft The Gospel upon the 10. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 10 Two men went up into the Temple to pray: the one a Pharisee, and the other a Publican.
\v 11 The Pharisee standing, prayed thus with himself: God, I give thee thanks that I am not as the rest of men, extortioners, unjust, adulterers, as also this Publican.
\v 12 I fast twice in a week: I give tithes of all that I possess. \f + \fr 18:12 \ft To take pride of fasting, tithing, or any good work, is naught: though the works themselves be very good.\f*
\v 13 And the Publican standing a far off would not so much as lift up his eyes toward Heaven; but he knocked his breast, saying: God be merciful to me a sinner. \f + \fr 18:13 \ft So do the Priests and people at the holy Altar knock their breasts, & say with the humble Publican, Deus propitius. August. Ps. 31. conc. 3.\f*
\v 14 Isay to you, this man went down into his house justified more than he: because every one that exalteth himself, shall be humbled; and he that humbleth himself, shall be exalted.
\v 15 And they brought unto him infants also, that he might touch them. Which thing when the Disciples saw, they rebuked them.
\v 16 But \sc Jesus\sc* calling them together, said: Suffer children to come unto me, and forbid them not, for the Kingdom of Heaven is for such.
\v 17 Amen I say to you: Whosoever receiveth not the Kingdom of God as a child, shall not enter into it. \f + \fr 18:17 \ft In matters of faith & religion we must be as humble & obedient to the Catholic Church as young children to their parents.\f*
\v 18 And a certain Prince asked him, saying: Good Master, by doing what, shall I possess everlasting life?
\v 19 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Why doest thou call me good? None is good but only God.
\v 20 Thou knowest the commandments: \add Thou shalt not kill, Thou shalt not commit adultery, Thou shalt not steal, Thou shalt not bear false witness, Honour thy father & mother.\add* \f + \fr 18:20 \ft Not faith only but also keeping the commandments purchase life everlasting. See annot. Mat. 19, 16.\f*
\v 21 Who said: All these things have I kept from my youth.
\v 22 Which \sc Jesus\sc* hearing, said to him: Yet one thing thou lackest: Sell all that ever thou hast, & give to the poor, and thou shalt have treasure in Heaven: and come follow me. \f + \fr 18:22 \ft This is not a commandment or precept, but counsel: which the religious do follow. See Annot. Mat. 19.\f*
\v 23 He hearing these things, was stroken sad: because he was very rich.
\v 24 And \sc Jesus\sc* seeing him stroken sad, said: How hardly shall they that have money enter into the Kingdom of God?
\v 25 For it is easier for a camel to pass through the eye of a needle, than for a rich man to enter into the Kingdom of God.
\v 26 And they that heard, said: And who can be saved?
\v 27 He said to them: The things that are impossible with men, are possible with God.
\v 28 And Peter said: Lo, we have left all things, and have followed thee.
\v 29 Who said to them: Amen I say to you, there is no man that hath left house, or parents, or brethren, or wife, or children for the Kingdom of God, \f + \fr 18:29 \ft The Apostles among other things left their wives also, as S. Hierom noteth out of this place. li. 1. adv. Iovin.\f*
\v 30 and shall not receive much more in this time, and in the world to come life everlasting. \f + \fr 18:30 \ft Life everlasting the reward for leaving or losing willingly our goods for Christ's sake.\f*
\v 31 And \sc Jesus\sc* took the Twelve, and said to them: Behold we go up to Jerusalem, and all things shall be consummate which were written by the Prophets of the Son of man. \f + \fr 18:31 \ft The Gospel upon the Sunday of Quinquagesima.\f*
\v 32 For he shall be delivered to the Gentiles, and shall be mocked, and scourged, and spit upon:
\v 33 and after they have scourged him, they will kill him, and the third day he shall rise again.
\v 34 And they understood none of these things, and this word was hid from them, and they understood not the things that were said.
\v 35 And it came to pass, when he drew nigh to Jericho, a certain blind man sat by the way, begging.
\v 36 And when he heard the multitude passing by, he asked what this should be.
\v 37 And they told him that \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth passed by.
\v 38 And he cried saying: \sc Jesus\sc* son of David, have mercy upon me.
\v 39 And they that went before, rebuked him, that he should hold his peace. But he cried much more, Son of David have mercy upon me.
\v 40 And \sc Jesus\sc* standing commanded him to be brought unto him. And when he was come near, he asked him,
\v 41 saying: What wilt thou that I do to thee? but he said: Lord, that I may see.
\v 42 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Do thou see; thy faith hath made thee whole.
\v 43 And forthwith he saw, and followed him, magnifying God. And all the people as they saw it, gave praise to God.
\c 19
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* entering in, he walked through Jericho. \f + \fr 19:1 \ft The Gospel in the Dedication of a Church, & Anniversary thereof.\f*
\v 2 And behold a man named Zachæus: and this was a Prince of the Publicans, and he rich.
\v 3 And he sought to see \sc Jesus\sc* what he was, and he could not for the multitude, because he was little of stature.
\v 4 And running before, he went up into a sycamore tree that he might see him: because he was to pass by it.
\v 5 And when he was come to the place, \sc Jesus\sc* looking up, saw him, and said to him: Zachæus come down in haste: because this day I must abide in thy house. \f + \fr 19:5 \ft Zachæus.\f*
\v 6 And he in haste came down, and received him rejoicing.
\v 7 And when all saw it, they murmured saying, that he turned in, to a man that was a sinner.
\v 8 But Zachæus standing, said to our Lord: Behold the half of my goods, Lord, I give to the poor: and if I have defrauded any man of any thing, I restore fourfold.
\v 9 \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: That this day salvation is made to this house: because that he also is the son of Abraham.
\v 10 For the Son of man is come to seek and to save that which was lost.
\v 11 They hearing these things, he added and spake a parable, for that he was nigh to Jerusalem, and because they thought that forthwith the Kingdom of God should be manifested.
\v 12 He said therefore: A certain noble man went into a far country to take to himself a kingdom, and to return. \f + \fr 19:12 \ft The Gospel for S. Lewis the King of France, August 25. And for some other Confessors not Bishops.\f*
\v 13 And calling his ten servants, he gave them ten pounds, and said to them: Occupy till I come.
\v 14 And his citizens hated him: and they sent a legacy after him, saying: We will not have this man reign over us.
\v 15 And it came to pass after he returned, having received his kingdom: and he commanded his servants to be called, to whom he gave the money; that he might know how much every man had gained by occupying.
\v 16 And the first came, saying: Lord thy pound hath gotten ten pounds.
\v 17 And he said to him: Well fare thee good servant, because thou hast been faithful in a little, thou shalt have power over ten cities. \f + \fr 19:17 \ft Mark here against the adversaries, that the rewards of these two good servants be diverse & unequal, according to the diversity or inequality of their gains, that is, their merits: & yet one receiveth the penny (Mt. 29, 9.) as well as the other, that is, heaven or life everlasting.\f*
\v 18 And the second came saying: Lord, thy pound hath made five pounds.
\v 19 And he said to him: And be thou over five cities.
\v 20 And another came, saying: Lord, lo here thy pound, which I have had laid up in a napkin.
\v 21 For I feared thee, because thou art an austere man: thou takest up that thou didst not set down, and thou reapest that which thou didst not sow.
\v 22 He saith to him: By thine own mouth I judge thee, naughty servant. Thou didst know that I am an austere man, taking up that I set not down, and reaping that which I sowed not:
\v 23 and why didst thou not give my money to the bank, and I coming might certes with usury have exacted it?
\v 24 And he said to them that stood by: Take the pound away from him, and give it to him that hath ten pounds \f + \fr 19:24 \ft See annotations Matth. 25, 29, &c.\f*
\v 25 And they said to him: Lord, he hath ten pounds.
\v 26 But I say to you, that to every one that hath shall be given: and from him that hath not, that also which he hath shall be taken from him.
\v 27 But as for those mine enemies that would not have me reign over them, bring them hither; and kill them before me.
\v 28 And having said these things, he went before ascending to Jerusalem. \f + \fr 19:28 \ft The fifth part of this Gospel. Of the Holy Week of his Passion in Hierusalem.\f*
\v 29 And it came to pass when he was come nigh to Bethphage and Bethania unto the mount called Olivet, he sent two of his Disciples,
\v 30 saying: Go into the town which is over against, into the which as you enter, you shall find the colt of an ass tied, on which no man ever hath sitten: loose him, and bring him. \f + \fr 19:30 \ft PALM SUNDAY.\f*
\v 31 And if any man ask you: Why loose you him? You shall say thus to him: Because our Lord needeth his service.
\v 32 And they that were sent, went their ways, and found as he said to them, the colt standing.
\v 33 And when they loosed the colt, the owners thereof said to them: Why loose you the colt?
\v 34 But they said: Because our Lord hath need of him.
\v 35 And they brought him to \sc Jesus\sc*. And casting their garments upon the colt, they set \sc Jesus\sc* thereupon.
\v 36 And as he went, they spread their garments underneath in the way.
\v 37 And when he approached now to the descent of mount-Olivet, all the multitudes of them that descended, began with joy to praise God with a loud voice, for all the miracles that they had seen, \f + \fr 19:37 \ft his disciples.\f*
\v 38 saying: Blessed is he that cometh King in the name of our Lord, peace in Heaven, and glory on high.
\v 39 And certain Pharisees of the multitudes said to him: Master, rebuke thy disciples.
\v 40 To whom he said: I say to you, that if these hold their peace, the stones shall cry.
\v 41 And as he drew near, seeing the city, he wept upon it, saying, \f + \fr 19:41 \ft The Gospel upon the 9. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 42 Because if thou also hadst known, and that in this thy day, the things that pertain to thy peace: but now they are hid from thine eyes.
\v 43 For the days shall come upon thee: and thy enemies shall compass thee with a trench, and inclose thee about, and straiten thee on every side, \f + \fr 19:43 \ft This was fulfilled 40. years after the death of Christ by Titus & Vespasianus, when besides incredible miseries of famine and other distresses, there perished eleven hundred thousand, and were taken captives 97000, the siege being in the very same feast & greatest solemnity of Easter when they put Christ to death. Euseb. li. 3. hist. c. 6. 7. 8. Ioseph. li. 7. c. 17.\f*
\v 44 and beat thee flat to the ground, and thy children that are in thee: and they shall not leave in thee a stone upon a stone, because thou hast not known the time of thy visitation.
\v 45 And entering into the Temple, he began to cast out the sellers therein and the buyers, \f + \fr 19:45 \ft MONDAY\f*
\v 46 saying to them: It is written, \add That my house is the house of prayer.\add* But you have \add made it a den of thieves.\add*
\v 47 And he was teaching daily in the Temple. And the chief Priests and the Scribes and the Princes of the people sought to destroy him:
\v 48 and they found not what to do to him. For all the people was suspense, hearing him.
\c 20
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass in one of the days, when he was teaching the people in the Temple & evangelizing, the chief Priests & the Scribes with the Ancients assembled, \f + \fr 20:1 \ft TUESDAY.\f*
\v 2 and spake saying to him, Tell us, in what power doest thou these things? Or, who is he that hath given thee this power?
\v 3 And \sc Jesus\sc* answering, said to them: I also will ask you one word. Answer me,
\v 4 The baptism of John was it from Heaven, or of men?
\v 5 But they thought within themselves, saying: That if we say, From Heaven, he will say: Why then did you not believe him?
\v 6 But if we say, of men, the whole people will stone us: for they are certain that John is a Prophet.
\v 7 And they answered that they knew not whence it was.
\v 8 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: Neither do I tell you in what power I do these things.
\v 9 And he began to say to the people this parable: A certain man planted a vineyard, & let it out to husbandmen: and he was from home a long time. \f + \fr 20:9 \ft See the marginal annotations Marc. 12.\f*
\v 10 And in time he sent to the husbandmen a servant, that they should give him of the fruit of the vineyard. Who beating him sent him away empty.
\v 11 And again he sent another servant. But they beating him also and reproachfully abusing him, sent him away empty.
\v 12 And again he sent the third: who wounding him also, cast him out.
\v 13 And the Lord of the vineyard said: What shall I do? I will send my beloved son: perhaps when they shall see him, they will reverence him.
\v 14 Whom when the husbandmen saw, they thought within themselves, saying: This is the heir, let us kill him, that the heritage may be ours.
\v 15 And casting him forth out of the vineyard, they killed him. What therefore will the Lord of the vineyard do to them?
\v 16 He will come, and will destroy these husbandmen, and will give the vineyard to others. Which they hearing, said to him: God forbid.
\v 17 But he beholding them said: What is this then that is written, \add The stone which the builders rejected, the same is become into the head of the corner?\add*
\v 18 Every one that falleth upon this stone, shall be quashed: and upon whom it shall fall, it shall break him to powder.
\v 19 And the chief Priests and Scribes sought to lay hands upon him that hour: and they feared the people, for they knew that he spake this similitude to them.
\v 20 And watching, they sent spies which should feign themselves just: that they might take him in his talk, and deliver him to the principality and power of the President.
\v 21 And they asked him, saying: Master, we know that thou speakest and teachest rightly; and thou doest not accept person, but teachest the way of God in truth.
\v 22 Is it lawful for us to give tribute to Cæsar, or not?
\v 23 But considering their guile, he said to them: Why tempt you me?
\v 24 Shew me a penny. Whose image hath it and inscription? They answering said: Cæsar's.
\v 25 And he said to them: Render therefore the things that are Cæsar's, to Cæsar: and the things that are God's, to God. \f + \fr 20:25 \ft So duties must be done to Princes, that our duty to God be not neglected. See Annot. Mat. c. 22, 21.\f*
\v 26 And they could not reprehend his word before the people: and marveling at his answer, they held their peace.
\v 27 And there came certain of the Sadducees, which deny that there is a resurrection, and they asked him,
\v 28 saying: Master, Moyses gave us in writing: If a man's brother die having a wife, and he have no children, that his brother take her to wife, and raise up seed to his brother.
\v 29 There were therefore seven brethren: and the first took a wife, and died without children.
\v 30 And the next took her, & he died without child.
\v 31 And the third took her. In like manner also all the seven, and they left no seed, and died.
\v 32 Last of all the woman died also.
\v 33 In the resurrection therefore, whose wife shall she be of them? Sithens the seven had her to wife.
\v 34 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: The children of this world marry, and are given in marriage:
\v 35 But they that shall be counted worthy of that world and the resurrection from the dead, neither marry, nor take wives; \f + \fr 20:35 \ft The Greek ὁι καταξιωθέντες importeth also this much, They that are made worthy, to wit, by the grace of God, and so they are indeed worthy: as also in the next chapter verse 36. & 2. Thess. 1, 5.\f*
\v 36 neither can they die any more, for they are equal to Angels: and they are the sons of God, seeing they are the sons of the resurrection.
\v 37 But that the dead rise again, Moyses also shewed, beside the bush, as he calleth the Lord: \add The God of Abraham, and the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob.\add*
\v 38 For God is not of the dead, but of the living: for all live to him.
\v 39 And certain of the Scribes answering, said to him: Master, thou hast said well.
\v 40 And further they durst not ask him anything.
\v 41 But he said to them: How say they that Christ is the son of David,
\v 42 and David himself saith in the book of Psalms: \add The Lord said to my Lord, sit on my right hand,\add*
\v 43 \add till I put thine enemies, the footstool of thy feet?\add*
\v 44 David then calleth him Lord: and how is he his son?
\v 45 And all the people hearing him, he said to his Disciples:
\v 46 Beware of the Scribes, that will walk in robes, and love salutations in the market-place, and the first chairs in the synagogues, and the chief rooms in feasts.
\v 47 Which devour widows' houses: feigning long prayer. These shall receive greater damnation.
\c 21
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* beholding, he saw them that did cast their gifts into the treasury, rich persons.
\v 2 And he saw also a certain poor widow casting two brass mites.
\v 3 And he said: Verily I say to you, that this poor widow hath cast more than all.
\v 4 For all these of their aboundance have cast into the gifts of God: but she of her penury, hath cast in all her living that she had.
\v 5 And certain saying of the temple that it was adorned with goodly stones and donaries, he said:
\v 6 These things which you see, the days will come wherein there shall not be left a stone upon a stone that shall not be destroyed. \f + \fr 21:6 \ft This was fulfilled 40 years after the death of Christ, the 19. of August, being the very month\f*
\v 7 And they asked him, saying: Master, when shall these things be: and what shall be the sign when they shall begin to come to pass? \f + \fr 21:7 \ft TUESDAY night.\f*
\v 8 Who said: See you be not seduced. For many will come in my name, saying that I am he: and the time is at hand, go not therefore after them. \f + \fr 21:8 \ft Many false-prophets & Heretics. See An. Mt. 24. Mr. 13.\f*
\v 9 And when you shall hear of wars and seditions, be not terrified: these things must first come to pass, but the end is not yet by and by. \f + \fr 21:9 \ft b The Gospel upon. SS. Vincentius' and Anastasius' day. Ian. 22. And for many Martyrs.\f*
\v 10 Then he said to them: Nation shall rise against nation, and kingdom against kingdom.
\v 11 And there shall be great earth-quakes in places, and pestilences and famines, and terrors from Heaven, and there shall be great signs.
\v 12 But before all these things they will lay their hands upon you: and persecute you delivering you into Synagogues and prisons, drawing you to kings and Presidents for my name. \f + \fr 21:12 \ft Great persecution of Catholic men.\f*
\v 13 and it shall happen unto you for testimony.
\v 14 Lay up this therefore in your hearts, not to premeditate how you shall answer.
\v 15 For I will give you mouth and wisdom, which all your adversaries shall not be able to resist and gainsay.
\v 16 And you shall be delivered up of your parents and brethren, and kinsmen and friends: and they will put to death of you.
\v 17 And you shall be odious to all men for my name:
\v 18 and a hair of your head shall not perish.
\v 19 In your patience you shall possess your souls.
\v 20 And when you shall see Jerusalem compassed about with an army, then know that the desolation thereof is at hand.
\v 21 then they that are in Jewry, let them flee to the mountains: and they in the midst thereof, let them depart: and they in the countries, let them not enter into it.
\v 22 For these are the days of vengeance, that all things may be fulfilled that are written.
\v 23 But woe to them that are with child & that give suck in those days. For there shall be great affliction upon the land, and wrath on this people.
\v 24 And they shall fall by the edge of the sword; and shall be led captive into all nations: and Jerusalem shall be trodden of the Gentiles, till the times of nations be fulfilled.
\v 25 And there shall be signs in the sun and the moon and the stars: and upon earth distress of nations, for the confusion of the sound of sea and waves, \f + \fr 21:25 \ft The Gospel upon the 1. Sunday in Advent.\f*
\v 26 men withering for fear and expectation, what shall come upon the whole world. For the powers of Heaven shall be moved:
\v 27 and then they shall see the Son of man coming in a cloud with great power and majesty.
\v 28 But when these things begin to come to pass, look up and lift up your heads: because your redemption is at hand.
\v 29 And he spake to them a similitude. See the figtree and all trees:
\v 30 when they now bud forth fruit out of themselves, you know that summer is nigh.
\v 31 So you also when you shall see these things come to pass, know that the Kingdom of God is nigh.
\v 32 Amen I say to you, that this generation shall not pass, till all be done.
\v 33 Heaven and earth shall pass; but my words shall not pass.
\v 34 And look well to yourselves, lest perhaps your hearts be overcharged with surfeiting and drunkenness and cares of this life: and that day come upon you suddenly.
\v 35 For as a snare shall it come upon all that sit upon the face of all the earth.
\v 36 Watch therefore, praying at all times, that you may be accounted worthy to escape all these things that are to come, and to stand before the Son of man. \f + \fr 21:36 \ft c ἵνα καταξιωθῆτε See Annot. c. 20. 35.\f*
\v 37 And the days he was teaching in the temple: but the nights going forth, he abode in the mount that is called Olivet. \f + \fr 21:37 \ft Solitariness or eremitage (as S. Gregory Nazian. saith) is a goodly thing: this doth the mount Carmel of Elias teach, John's desert, & that mount unto which JESUS often retired, & was quietly alone with himself. Ser. 26. de amore pauperum.\f*
\v 38 And all the people in the morning went unto him in the temple to hear him.
\c 22
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* the festival day of the Azymes approached, which is called Pasch: \f + \fr 22:1 \ft The PASSION according to S. Luke in these two chapters, is the Gospel at Mass upon Tenebræ Wednesday. TENEBRÆ Wednesday.\f*
\v 2 & the chief Priests & the Scribes sought how they might kill him: but they feared the people.
\v 3 And Satan entered into Judas that was surnamed Iscariote, one of the Twelve.
\v 4 And he went, and talked with the chief Priests and the Magistrates, how he might betray him to them.
\v 5 And they were glad, and bargained to give him money.
\v 6 And he promised. And he sought opportunity to betray him apart from the multitudes.
\v 7 And the day of the Azymes came, wherein it was necessary that the Pasch should be killed. \f + \fr 22:7 \ft MAUNDY Thursday.\f*
\v 8 And he sent Peter and John, saying: Go and prepare us the Pasch, that we may eat.
\v 9 But they said: Where wilt thou that we prepare it?
\v 10 And he said to them: Behold, as you enter into the city, there shall meet you a man carrying a pitcher of water: follow him into the house into which he entereth,
\v 11 and you shall say to the good-man of the house: The Master saith to thee, where is the inn where I may eat the Pasch with my Disciples?
\v 12 And he will shew you a great refectory adorned: and there prepare.
\v 13 And they going, found as he said to them, and prepared the Pasch.
\v 14 And when the hour was come, he sat down, and the twelve Apostles with him.
\v 15 And he said to them: With desire I have desired to eat this Pasch with you before I suffer.
\v 16 For I say to you, that from this time I will not eat it, till it be fulfilled in the Kingdom of God.
\v 17 And taking the chalice he gave thanks, and said: Take and divide among you.
\v 18 For I say to you, that I will not drink of the generation of the vine, till the Kingdom of God do come.
\v 19 And taking bread, he gave thanks, and brake; and gave to them, saying: \sc This is my Body Which is Given For You\sc*. Do this for a commemoration of me.
\v 20 In like manner the chalice also, after he had supped, saying: \sc This is The Chalice The New Testament in my Blood, Which Shall be Shed For You\sc*. \f + \fr 22:20 \ft The Greek is here so plain, that there was very blood in the chalice, shed for us, that Beza saith it is a corruption in the Greek. See the Annota. upon this place.\f*
\v 21 But yet behold, the hand of him that betrayeth me, is with me on the table.
\v 22 And the Son of man indeed goeth according to that which is determined: but yet woe to that man by whom he shall be betrayed.
\v 23 And they began to question among themselves, which of them it should be that should do this.
\v 24 And there fell also a contention between them, which of them seemed to be greater. \f + \fr 22:24 \ft The Gospel upon S. Apollinaris' day. Iulij 23.\f*
\v 25 And he said to them: The Kings of the Gentiles overrule them; and they that have power upon them, are called beneficial.
\v 26 But you not so: but he that is the greater among you, let him become as the younger: & he that is the leader, as the waiter.
\v 27 For which is greater, he that sitteth at the table, or he that ministereth? Is not he that sitteth? But I am in the midst of you, as he that ministereth:
\v 28 & you are they that have remained with me in my tentations.
\v 29 And I dispose to you, as my Father disposed to me, a Kingdom:
\v 30 that you may eat & drink upon my table in my Kingdom, & may sit upon thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel. \f + \fr 22:30 \ft Straight after the former loving check & admonition, he promiseth to them all that have been partakers with him of his miseries in this life, greater preeminence in heaven, than any Potentate can have in this world, & therefore that they need not be careful of dignity or Supremacy.\f*
\v 31 And our Lord said: Simon, Simon, behold Satan hath required to have you for to sift as wheat:
\v 32 \sc But I have Prayed For Thee\sc*, that thy faith fail not: and thou once converted, confirm thy brethren.
\v 33 Who said to him: Lord, with thee I am ready to go both into prison and unto death.
\v 34 And he said: I say to thee Peter, the cock shall not crow today, till thou deny thrice that thou knowest me.
\v 35 And he said to them: When I sent you without purse and scrip and shoes, did you lack any thing? But they said: Nothing.
\v 36 He said therefore unto them: But now he that hath a purse, let him take it, likewise also a scrip: and he that hath not, let him sell his coat, and buy a sword.
\v 37 For I say to you, that yet this that is written must be fulfilled in me: \add And with the wicked was he reputed.\add* For those things that are concerning me, have an end.
\v 38 But they said: Lord, lo two swords here. But he said to them: It is enough.
\v 39 And going forth he went according to his custom into mount-Olivet. And his Disciples also followed him.
\v 40 And when he was come to the place, he said to them: Pray, lest ye enter into tentation. \f + \fr 22:40 \ft THURSDAY night.\f*
\v 41 And he was pulled away from them a stone's cast: and kneeling he prayed,
\v 42 saying: Father, if thou wilt, transfer this chalice from me. But yet not my will, but thine be done.
\v 43 And there appeared to him an Angel from Heaven, strengthening him. And being in an agony, he prayed the longer.
\v 44 And his sweat became as drops of blood trickling down upon the earth.
\v 45 And when he was risen up from prayer, and was come to his Disciples, he found them sleeping for pensiveness.
\v 46 And he said to them: Why sleep you? Arise, pray, lest you enter into tentation.
\v 47 As he was yet speaking, behold a multitude: and he that was called Judas, one of the Twelve, went before them, and approached to \sc Jesus\sc*, for to kiss him.
\v 48 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Judas with a kiss doest thou betray the Son of man?
\v 49 And they that were about him, seeing what would be, said to him: Lord, shall we strike with the sword?
\v 50 And one of them smote the servant of the high Priest: and cut off his right ear.
\v 51 But \sc Jesus\sc* answering, said: Suffer ye thus far. And when he had touched his ear, he healed him.
\v 52 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to them that were come unto him, the chief Priests, and magistrates of the temple, & ancients: As it were to a thief are you come forth with swords and clubs?
\v 53 When I was daily with you in the temple, you did not lay hands upon me, but this is your hour, and the power of darkness.
\v 54 And apprehending him, they led him to the high Priest's house: but Peter followed a far off.
\v 55 And a fire being kindled in the midst of the court, & they sitting about it, Peter was in the midst of them.
\v 56 Whom when a certain wench saw sitting at the light, and had beheld him, she said: This fellow also was with him.
\v 57 But he denied him, saying: Woman, I know him not.
\v 58 And after a while another man seeing him, said: And thou art of them. But Peter said: O man I am not.
\v 59 And after the space as it were of one hour, a certain other man affirmed, saying: Verily this fellow also was with him: for he is also a Galilæan.
\v 60 And Peter said: Man I know not what thou sayest. And incontinent as he was yet speaking, the cock crew.
\v 61 And our Lord turning looked on Peter. And Peter remembered the word of our Lord, as he had said: That before the cock crow, thou shalt thrice deny me.
\v 62 And Peter going forth a doors, wept bitterly.
\v 63 And the men that held him, mocked him, beating him.
\v 64 And they did blind-fold him, and smote his face. And they asked him saying: Prophesy, who is it that smote thee?
\v 65 And blaspheming many other things they said against him.
\v 66 And when it was day, there assembled the Ancients of the people and chief Priests and Scribes, and they brought him into their Council, saying:
\v 67 If thou be Christ tell us. And he said to them: If I tell you, you will not believe me:
\v 68 if also I ask, you will not answer me, nor dismiss me.
\v 69 But from henceforth the Son of man shall be sitting on the right hand of the power of God.
\v 70 And they all said: Art thou then the Son of God? Who said: You say that I am.
\v 71 But they said: What need we testimony any further? For ourselves have heard of his own mouth.
\c 23
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* all the multitude of them rising up, led him to Pilate. \f + \fr 23:1 \ft GOOD FRIDAY.\f*
\v 2 And they began to accuse him, saying: We have found this man subverting our nation, & prohibiting to give tributes to Cæsar, and saying that he is Christ the King.
\v 3 And Pilate asked him, saying: Art thou the King of the Jews? But he answering said: Thou sayest.
\v 4 And Pilate said to the chief Priests and multitudes: I find no cause in this man.
\v 5 But they were more earnest, saying: He stirreth the people teaching throughout all Jewry, beginning from Galilee even hither.
\v 6 But Pilate hearing Galilee, asked if the man were of Galilee.
\v 7 And when he understood that he was of Herod's jurisdiction, he sent him back to Herod, who was also himself at Jerusalem in those days.
\v 8 And Herod seeing \sc Jesus\sc*, was very glad, for he was desirous of a long time to see him, for because he heard many things of him: and he hoped to see some sign wrought by him.
\v 9 And he asked him in many words. But he answered him nothing.
\v 10 And there stood the chief Priests and the Scribes constantly accusing him.
\v 11 And Herod with his army set him at naught: and he mocked him, putting on him a white garment, and sent him back to Pilate.
\v 12 And Herod and Pilate were made friends that day. For before they were enemies one to another.
\v 13 And Pilate calling together the chief Priests and Magistrates, and the people,
\v 14 said to them: You have presented unto me this man, as averting the people, and behold I examining him before you, have found no cause in this man of those things, wherein you accuse him.
\v 15 No, nor Herod neither. For I sent you to him, and behold, nothing worthy of death is done to him.
\v 16 I will chasten him therefore and dismiss him.
\v 17 And he of necessity had to release unto them upon the feast day, one.
\v 18 But the whole multitude together cried out, saying: Dispatch him, and release us Barabbas.
\v 19 Who was for a certain sedition made in the city and murder, cast into prison.
\v 20 And Pilate again spake to them, desirous to release \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 21 But they cried again, saying: Crucify, crucify him.
\v 22 And he the third time said to them: Why, what evil hath this man done? I find no cause of death in him. I will correct him therefore & let him go.
\v 23 But they were instant with loud voices requiring that he might be crucified. And their voices prevailed.
\v 24 And Pilate adjudged their petition to be done.
\v 25 And he released unto them him that for murder and sedition had been cast into prison, whom they demanded: but \sc Jesus\sc* he delivered to their pleasure.
\v 26 And when they led him, they took one Simon of Cyrene coming from the country: and they laid the Cross upon him to carry after \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 27 And there followed him a great multitude of people, and of women which bewailed and lamented him.
\v 28 But \sc Jesus\sc* turning to them, said: Daughters of Jerusalem, weep not upon me, but weep upon yourselves, and upon your children.
\v 29 For behold the days shall come, wherein they will say: Blessed are the barren, and the wombs that have not born, & the paps that have not given suck.
\v 30 \add Then shall they begin to say to the mountains, Fall upon us: and to the hills, Cover us.\add*
\v 31 For if in the green wood they do these things, in the dry what shall be done?
\v 32 And there were led also other two malefactors with him, to be executed.
\v 33 And after they came to the place which is called Calvary, there they crucified him: and the thieves, one on the right hand and the other on the left.
\v 34 And \sc Jesus\sc* said: Father, forgive them, for they know not what they do. But they dividing his garments, did cast lots.
\v 35 And the people stood beholding, and the Princes with them derided him, saying: Others he hath saved, let him save himself, if this be Christ, the elect of God. \f + \fr 23:35 \ft expecting.\f*
\v 36 And the soldiers also mocked him coming to him, and offering him vinegar,
\v 37 saying: If thou be the King of the Jews, save thyself.
\v 38 And there was also a superscription written over him in Greek, and Latin, and Hebrew letters: \sc This is The King of The Jews\sc*.
\v 39 And one of those thieves that were hanged, blasphemed him, saying: If thou be Christ, save thyself, and us.
\v 40 But the other answering, rebuked him, saying: Neither doest thou fear God, where as thou art in the same damnation?
\v 41 And we indeed justly, for we receive worthy of our doings: but this man hath done no evil.
\v 42 And he said to \sc Jesus\sc*: Lord, remember me when thou shalt come into thy Kingdom.
\v 43 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Amen I say to thee; this day thou shalt be with me in Paradise.
\v 44 And it was almost the sixth hour: and there was made darkness upon the whole earth until the ninth hour.
\v 45 And the sun was darkened; and the veil of the temple was rent in the midst. \f + \fr 23:45 \ft This eclipse was seen and wondered at as a thing above nature, of Dionysius Areopagita at Thebes, when he was yet a Pagan. Dionys. ep. ad Policarp & ep. ad Apollophanem.\f*
\v 46 And \sc Jesus\sc* crying with a loud voice, said: \add Father, into thy hands I commend my Spirit.\add* And saying this, he gave up the ghost.
\v 47 And the Centurion seeing that which was done, glorified God, saying: Indeed this man was just.
\v 48 And all the multitude of them that were present together at that sight, and saw the things that were done, returned knocking their breasts.
\v 49 And all his acquaintance stood a far off, and the women that had followed him from Galilee, seeing these things.
\v 50 And behold a man named Joseph, which was a Senator, a good man and a just.
\v 51 He had not consented to their counsel and doings, of Arimathæa a city of Jewry, who also himself expected the Kingdom of God.
\v 52 This man came to Pilate, and asked the body of \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 53 And taking it down, wrapped it in sindon, and laid him in a monument hewed of stone, wherein never yet any man had been laid.
\v 54 And it was the day of Parasceve, and the Sabboth drew near.
\v 55 And the women that were come with him from Galilee, following after, saw the monument, and how his body was laid.
\v 56 And returning they prepared spices and ointments: and on the Sabboth they rested according to the commandment.
\c 24
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* in the first of the Sabboth very early they came to the monument, carrying the spices which they had prepared. \f + \fr 24:1 \ft EASTER DAY.\f* \f + \fr 24:1 \ft That is, first after the Sabboth, which is (saith S. Hiero. q. 4. ad Hedib.) dies Dominica, our Lord's day, wherein he arose. For the week is divided into the Sabboth, & the 1. 2. 3. 4. 5. 6. of the Sabboth. And the Apostle (1. Cor. 16, 2.) commanded a collection of money to be made on the first of the Sabboth. Whereby we learn, both the keeping of Sunday, & the Church's count of days by the 2. 3. 4. of the Sabboth, to be Apostolical. Which S. Sylvester afterward named, 2. 3. 4. feriam &c. Breviar. Roman. Decemb. 31.\f*
\v 2 And they found the stone rolled back from the monument.
\v 3 And going in, they found not the body of our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 4 And it came to pass, as they were astonished in their mind at this, behold two men stood beside them in glistering apparel.
\v 5 And when they feared and cast down their countenance toward the ground, they said unto them: Why seek you the living with the dead?
\v 6 he is not here, but is risen. Remember how he spake to you, when he yet was in Galilee,
\v 7 saying: That the Son of man must be delivered into the hands of sinners and be crucified, and the third day rise again.
\v 8 And they remembered his words.
\v 9 And going back from the monument, they told all these things to those eleven, and to all the rest.
\v 10 And it was Mary Magdalene, and Joane, and Mary of James, and the rest that were with them, which said these things to the Apostles.
\v 11 And these words seemed before them as dotage, and they did not believe them.
\v 12 But Peter rising up ran to the monument; and stooping down he saw the linen cloths lying alone, and went away marveling with himself at that which was done.
\v 13 And behold, two of them went the same day into a town which was the space of sixty furlongs from Jerusalem, named Emmaus. \f + \fr 24:13 \ft The Gospel upon Monday in Easter week.\f*
\v 14 And they talked betwixt themselves of all those things that had chanced.
\v 15 And it came to pass, while they talked and reasoned with themselves, \sc Jesus\sc* also himself approaching went with them.
\v 16 But their eyes were held that they might not know him.
\v 17 And he said to them: What are these communications that you confer one with another walking, and are sad?
\v 18 And one whose name was Cleophas, answering, said to him: Art thou only a stranger in Jerusalem, and hast not known the things that have been done in it, these days?
\v 19 To whom he said: What things? And they said, concerning \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth, who was a man a Prophet, mighty in work and word before God and all the people.
\v 20 And how our chief Priests and Princes delivered him into condemnation of death, and crucified him.
\v 21 But we hoped that it was he that should redeem Israel: and now besides all this, today is the third day since these things were done.
\v 22 But certain women also of ours, made us afraid: who before it was light, were at the monument,
\v 23 and not finding his body, came, saying that they saw a vision also of Angels, who say that he is alive.
\v 24 And certain men of ours went to the monument: and they found it so as the women said, but him they found not.
\v 25 And he said to them: O foolish, and slow of heart to believe in all things which the Prophets have spoken.
\v 26 Ought not Christ to have suffered these things, and so to enter into his glory?
\v 27 And beginning from Moyses and all the Prophets, he did interpret to them in all the scriptures the things that were concerning him.
\v 28 And they drew nigh to the town whither they went: and he made semblance to go further.
\v 29 And they forced him, saying: Tarry with us, because it is toward night, and the day is now far spent. And he went in with them.
\v 30 And it came to pass, whiles he sat at the table with them, he took bread, and blessed and brake, and did reach to them.
\v 31 And their eyes were opened, and they knew him: and he vanished out of their sight.
\v 32 And they said one to the other: Was not our heart burning in us, whiles he spake in the way, and opened unto us the scriptures?
\v 33 And rising up the same hour they went back into Jerusalem: and they found the eleven gathered together, and those that were with them,
\v 34 saying: That our Lord is risen indeed, and hath appeared to Simon.
\v 35 And they told the things that were done in the way: and how they knew him in the breaking of bread.
\v 36 And whiles they speak these things, \sc Jesus\sc* stood in the midst of them, and he saith to them: Peace be to you; it is I, fear not. \f + \fr 24:36 \ft The Gospel upon Tuesday in Easter week.\f*
\v 37 But they being troubled and frighted, imagined that they saw a Spirit.
\v 38 And he said to them: Why are you troubled, and cogitations arise into your hearts?
\v 39 See my hands, and feet, that it is I myself: handle, and see: for a Spirit hath not flesh and bones, as you see me to have.
\v 40 And when he had said this, he shewed them his hands and feet.
\v 41 But they yet not believing and marveling for joy, he said: Have you here any thing to be eaten?
\v 42 But they offered him a piece of fish broiled, and a honey comb.
\v 43 And when he had eaten before them, taking the remains he gave to them.
\v 44 And he said to them: These are the words which I spake to you, when I was yet with you, that all things must needs be fulfilled, which are written in the law of Moyses, and the Prophets, and the Psalms, of me.
\v 45 Then he opened their understanding, that they might understand the Scriptures.
\v 46 And he said to them: That so it is written, and so it behoved Christ to suffer, and to rise again from the dead the third day:
\v 47 and penance to be preached in his name and remission of sins unto all nations, beginning from Jerusalem. \f + \fr 24:47 \ft As he shall be Anathema (saith S. Aug.) which preacheth that Christ neither suffered nor rose again, because we learn by the Gospel, That it behoved Christ to suffer and to rise again the third day: so he shall also be Anathema, whosoever preacheth the Church to be\f*
\v 48 And you are witnesses of these things.
\v 49 And I send the promise of my Father upon you: but you, tarry in the city, till you be endued with power from high.
\v 50 And he brought them forth abroad into Bethania: and lifting up his hands he blessed them. \f + \fr 24:50 \ft ASCENSION DAY.\f*
\v 51 And it came to pass whiles he blessed them, he departed from them, and was carried into Heaven.
\v 52 And they adoring went back into Jerusalem with great joy:
\v 53 and they were always in the temple praising and blessing God. Amen.
